# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: assisted-natural-regeneration
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] US$5 billion in funding for a project called the "Protecting Our Planet Challenge" was announced for the initiative in September 2021.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] In December 2022, 30 by 30 was agreed at the COP15 meeting of the Convention on Biological Diversity, and became a target of the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] This includes the G7 and European Union.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] The initiative has attracted controversy over indigenous rights issues.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] As of May 2026, 17.3% of terrestrial land and inland waters and 9.8% of marine areas are protected.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] Including OECM's (Other Effective Area-based Conservation Measures) the percent of protected areas are 18.4% of terrestrial and inland waters and 10.0% of marine areas.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] The European Commission's Biodiversity strategy for 2030 was proposed on May 20, 2020, as the European Union's contribution to a post-2020 global biodiversity framework.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] The plan includes turning 30% of EU territory to protected area by 2030 and 10% to strictly protected area.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] However as of 2023 EU is not on track to meet the targets.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] The biodiversity strategy is a core part of the European Green Deal, and also intended to support green recovery from the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] In July 2023 after many debates the European parliament adopted a version of the Nature restoration law, aiming to restore nature on 20% of the territory of the European Union by 2030.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] In 2024, the European Union passed a nature restoration law aiming to restore 20% of degraded ecosystems by 2030 and 100% by 2050.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] On January 27, 2021, President Joe Biden issued an executive order on "Tackling the Climate Crisis at Home and Abroad".
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] Participating federal agencies included the U.S.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] Department of Commerce, and Council on Environmental Quality.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] The order also established a California Biodiversity Collaborative composed of representatives of government agencies, Native tribes, experts, and other stakeholders.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] The official report, *Pathways to 30x30 California*, was issued by the California Natural Resources Agency on 22 April 2022.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] Implementation of the 30 by 30 target has progressed unevenly, and researchers caution that simply increasing the extent of protected areas is not sufficient to halt biodiversity loss.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] Some conservationists argue that the 30% figure lacks a clear scientific justification and risks being treated as a symbolic or political benchmark rather than a threshold grounded in ecological evidence.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] At the same time, other researchers and advocacy groups contend that 30% may in fact be too low to secure long‑term ecological integrity, and point to proposals such as the "Half‑Earth" concept, which calls for roughly 50% of terrestrial and marine realms to be conserved in some form.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] A further concern relates to the quality and effectiveness of protection once areas are designated.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] Researchers and NGOs have highlighted the persistence of so‑called "paper parks": protected areas that exist in law but lack adequate funding, staffing or enforcement, allowing activities such as poaching, illegal logging, or unregulated development to continue.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] Modelling work by Kuempel et al. suggests that, for exploited species, improving enforcement and management within existing protected areas can in many cases deliver greater conservation benefits than simply expanding the network’s total area without a corresponding increase in resources.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] Taken together, this literature underlines that meeting percentage‑based targets without adequate governance capacity risks diluting scarce conservation resources.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] Other research has examined conditions under which expanding protected areas can still be beneficial even when management budgets do not increase.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] Their results suggest that, in landscapes where human pressures are spatially clumped near reserve boundaries, strategically increasing the size of protected areas can create more secure habitat refuges even without proportional increases in staffing or enforcement.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] In practice, the 30 by 30 commitment has also prompted debate over how "protected" or "conserved" areas are defined for monitoring and reporting purposes.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] Implementation of the 30 by 30 target has also raised concerns about “green grabbing” and green colonialism in the way new protected and conserved areas may be established.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] Similar critiques have been echoed by human rights organisations and researchers who argue that percentage-based conservation targets can replicate earlier "fortress conservation" models if they are implemented through top-down land designations that disregard customary tenure and existing uses.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] More broadly, some Indigenous organisations have criticised the way 30 by 30 has been promoted and negotiated, arguing that it risks appropriating Indigenous lands under the guise of biodiversity conservation.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] The COP15 included 196 parties in negotiations, with competing views regarding the adoption of the 30 by 30 target being wide-spread and well documented.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] The resulting agreement of the conference, the Convention on Biological Diversity, was signed by every party, with the exception of two: the United States and the Vatican.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] Towards the end of the talks, a negotiator from Democratic Republic of the Congo raised objections to the agreement, citing a lack of funding separate from the current Global Environment Facility (GEF).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] After a delay, COP15 president and Chinese environment minister Huang Runqiu overruled the objection due to a legal technicality, resulting in the passage of the agreement.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] Delegates from the DRC, Cameroon, and Uganda were reportedly displeased with the outcome.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/30-by-30] After the agreement was passed, the DRC's government announced that it would not recognize it as valid.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] In comparison, reforestation means re-establishing forest that have either been cut down or lost due to natural causes, such as fire, storm, etc.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Nowadays, the boundaries between afforestation and reforestation projects can be blurred as it may not be so clear what was there before at what point in time.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] An essential aspect of successful afforestation efforts lies in the careful selection of tree species that are well-suited to the local climate and soil conditions.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] By choosing appropriate species, afforested areas can better withstand the impacts of climate change.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Earth offers enough room to plant an additional 0.9 billion ha of tree canopy cover.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Planting and protecting them would sequester 205 billion tons of carbon which is about 20 years of current global carbon emissions.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] This level of sequestration would represent about 25% of the atmosphere's current carbon pool.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] However, there has been debate about whether afforestation is beneficial for the sustainable use of natural resources, with some researchers pointing out that tree planting is not the only way to enhance climate mitigation and CO2 capture.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Non-forest areas, such as grasslands and savannas, also benefit the biosphere and humanity, and they need a different management strategy - they are not supposed to be forests.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Afforestation critics argue that ecosystems without trees are not necessarily degraded, and many of them can store carbon as they are; for example, savannas and tundra store carbon underground.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Carbon sequestration estimates in these areas often do not include the total amount of carbon reductions in soils and slowing tree growth over time.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Afforestation can also negatively affect biodiversity by increasing fragmentation and edge effects on the habitat outside the planted area.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Australia, Canada, China, India, Israel, United States and Europe have afforestation programs to increase carbon dioxide removal in forests and in some cases to reduce desertification.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] The term afforestation means establishing new forest on lands that were not forest before (e.g. abandoned agriculture).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] The same definition in other words states that afforestation is "conversion to forest of land that historically has not contained forests".
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] In comparison, reforestation means the "conversion to forest of land that has previously contained forests but that has been converted to some other use".
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Agroforestry (this is essentially an agricultural activity carried out in order to grow harvestable crops such as fruits and nuts).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Tree plantations (carried out in order to produce wood and wood-pulp products; this can be seen as an alternative to cutting down naturally occurring forests).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] However, the term *afforestation* can also "imply the intentional conversion of native non-forest ecosystems to exotic tree cover and violate biodiversity safeguards".
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] The process of afforestation begins with site selection.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Several environmental factors of the site must be analyzed, including climate, soil, vegetation, and human activity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] These factors will determine the quality of the site, what species of trees should be planted, and what planting method should be used.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] After the forest site has been assessed, the area must be prepared for planting.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Preparation can involve a variety of mechanical or chemical methods, such as chopping, mounding, bedding, herbicides, and prescribed burning.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Once the site is prepared, planting can take place.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] One method for planting is direct seeding, which involves sowing seeds directly into the forest floor.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Another is seedling planting, which is similar to direct seeding except that seedlings already have an established root system.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Afforestation by cutting is an option for tree species that can reproduce asexually, where a piece of a tree stem, branch, root, or leaves can be planted onto the forest floor and sprout successfully.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Sometimes special tools, such as a tree planting bar, are used to make planting of trees easier and faster.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] There are several benefits from afforestation such as carbon sequestration, increasing rainfall, prevention of topsoil erosion (from water and wind), flood and landslide mitigation, barriers against high winds, shelter for wildlife, employment and alternative sources of wood products.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Afforestation projects create employment opportunities, particularly in rural areas, thus promoting sustainable livelihoods.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] They can create many jobs in various forest-related activities.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Forests are an important part of the global carbon cycle because trees and plants absorb carbon dioxide through photosynthesis.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Therefore, they play an important role in climate change mitigation.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] By removing the greenhouse gas CO2 from the air, forests function as terrestrial carbon sinks, meaning they store large amounts of carbon in the form of biomass, encompassing roots, stems, branches, and leaves.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] By doing so, forests sequester approximately 25% of human carbon emissions annually, playing a critical role in Earth's climate.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Throughout their lifespan, trees continue to sequester carbon, storing atmospheric CO2 long-term.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Sustainable forest management, afforestation, reforestation are therefore important contributions to climate change mitigation.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] An important consideration in such efforts is that forests can turn from sinks to carbon sources.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] In 2019 forests took up a third less carbon than they did in the 1990s, due to higher temperatures, droughts and deforestation.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] National-scale forest inventory data also shows trends from 1999 to 2020 that some forests were already approaching climate thresholds shifting them from carbon sinks to carbon sources.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] The typical tropical forest may become a carbon source by the 2060s.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Researchers have found that, in terms of environmental services, it is better to avoid deforestation than to allow for deforestation to subsequently reforest, as the latter leads to irreversible effects in terms of biodiversity loss and soil degradation.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Furthermore, the probability that legacy carbon will be released from soil is higher in a younger boreal forest.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] In particular, boreal forests have been noted to support the growth of Armillaria (honey fungus), which is a root pathogen that breaks down compounds necessary for wood integrity, increasing the likelihood of carbon release.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Global greenhouse gas emissions caused by damage to tropical rainforests may have been substantially underestimated until around 2019.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Additionally, the effects of afforestation and reforestation will be farther in the future than keeping existing forests intact.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] It takes much longer − several decades − for the benefits for global warming to manifest to the same carbon sequestration benefits from mature trees in tropical forests and hence from limiting deforestation.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Therefore, scientists consider "the protection and recovery of carbon-rich and long-lived ecosystems, especially natural forests" to be "the major climate solution".
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] The planting of trees on marginal crop and pasture lands helps to incorporate carbon from atmospheric CO 2 into biomass.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] For this carbon sequestration process to succeed the carbon must not return to the atmosphere from biomass burning or rotting when the trees die.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Several species of *Ficus* such as *Ficus wakefieldii* have been observed to sequester atmospheric CO2 as calcium oxalate in the presence of oxalotrophic bacteria and fungi, which catabolize the oxalate, which produces calcium carbonate.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] The calcium carbonate is precipitated throughout the tree, which also alkalinizes the surrounding soil.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] These species are current candidates for carbon sequestration in agroforestry.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] This Calcium-oxalate fixation process was first observed in the *Iroko* tree, which can sequester up to a ton of calcium carbonate in the soil over its lifespan.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Also Cacti, such as the *Saguaro*, transfer carbon from the biological cycle to the geological cycle by forming the mineral calcium carbonate.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Earth offers enough room to plant an additional 0.9 billion ha of tree canopy cover, although this estimate has been criticized, and the true area that has a net cooling effect on the climate when accounting for biophysical feedbacks like albedo is 20-80% lower.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Planting and protecting these trees would sequester 205 billion tons of carbon if the trees survive future climate stress to reach maturity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] To put this number into perspective, this is about 20 years of current global carbon emissions (as of 2019) .
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] This level of sequestration would represent about 25% of the atmosphere's carbon pool in 2019.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Life expectancy of forests varies throughout the world, influenced by tree species, site conditions, and natural disturbance patterns.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] In some forests, carbon may be stored for centuries, while in other forests, carbon is released with frequent stand replacing fires.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Forests that are harvested prior to stand replacing events allow for the retention of carbon in manufactured forest products such as lumber.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] However, only a portion of the carbon removed from logged forests ends up as durable goods and buildings.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] The remainder ends up as sawmill by-products such as pulp, paper, and pallets.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] If all new construction globally utilized 90% wood products, largely via adoption of mass timber in low rise construction, this could sequester 700 million net tons of carbon per year.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] This is in addition to the elimination of carbon emissions from the displaced construction material such as steel or concrete, which are carbon-intense to produce.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] A meta-analysis found that mixed species plantations would increase carbon storage alongside other benefits of diversifying planted forests.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Although a bamboo forest stores less total carbon than a mature forest of trees, a bamboo plantation sequesters carbon at a much faster rate than a mature forest or a tree plantation.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Therefore, the farming of bamboo timber may have significant carbon sequestration potential.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that: "The total carbon stock in forests decreased from 668 gigatonnes in 1990 to 662 gigatonnes in 2020".
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] In Canada's boreal forests as much as 80% of the total carbon is stored in the soils as dead organic matter.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Impacts on temperature are affected by the location of the forest.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] For example, reforestation in boreal or subarctic regions has less impact on climate.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] This is because it substitutes a high-albedo, snow-dominated region with a lower-albedo forest canopy.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] By contrast, tropical reforestation projects lead to a positive change such as the formation of clouds.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] These clouds then reflect the sunlight, lowering temperatures.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Planting trees in tropical climates with wet seasons has another advantage.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] In such a setting, trees grow more quickly (fixing more carbon) because they can grow year-round.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Trees in tropical climates have, on average, larger, brighter, and more abundant leaves than non-tropical climates.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] A study of the girth of 70,000 trees across Africa has shown that tropical forests fix more carbon dioxide pollution than previously realized.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] The research suggested almost one-fifth of fossil fuel emissions are absorbed by forests across Africa, Amazonia and Asia.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Afforestation provides other environmental benefits, including increasing the soil quality and its organic carbon levels, reducing the risk of erosion and desertification.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] The planting of trees in urban areas is also able to reduce air pollution via the trees' absorption and filtration of pollutants, including carbon monoxide, sulfur dioxide, and ozone, in addition to CO2.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Afforestation protects the biodiversity of plants and animals which allows the sustenance of ecosystems that provide clean air, soil fertilization, etc.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Forests support biodiversity conservation, providing habitats for about 80% of the world's biodiversity and contributing to ecosystem restoration and resilience.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Water management can be improved afforestation, as trees regulate hydrological cycles, reduce soil erosion, and prevent water runoff.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Their capacity to capture and store water helps in mitigating floods and droughts.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Forests act as natural air filters, absorbing pollutants and improving air quality.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Urban forestation projects have been successful in reducing respiratory illnesses and enhancing overall air quality in cities.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Trees provide shade and cooling effects.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] By shading and evaporation, forests can lower local temperatures, offering a more comfortable environment in urban areas and reducing the impact of extreme heat.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Tree-planting campaigns are criticised for sometimes targeting areas where forests would not naturally occur, such as grassland and savanna biomes.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Carbon sequestration forecasts of afforestation programmes often insufficiently consider possible carbon reductions in soils as well as slowing tree growth over time.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Afforestation can negatively affect biodiversity through increasing fragmentation and edge effects for the habitat remaining outside the planted area.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] New forest plantations can introduce generalist predators that would otherwise not be found in open habitat into the covered area, which could detrimentally increase predation rates on the native species of the area.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] A study by scientists at the British Trust for Ornithology into the decline of British populations of Eurasian curlew found that afforestation had impacted curlew populations through fragmentation of their naturally open grassland habitats and increases in generalist predators.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Questions have also been raised in the scientific community regarding how global afforestation could affect the surface albedo of Earth.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] The canopy cover of mature trees could make the surface albedo darker, which causes more heat to be absorbed, potentially raising the temperature of the planet.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] This is particularly relevant in parts of the world with high levels of snow cover, due to the significant difference in albedo between highly reflective white snow and darker forest cover which absorbs more solar radiation.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] One significant criticism of reforestation or afforestation efforts that rely on monocultures of - usually conifer - trees is that, while they may increase tree cover, they fail to provide the diverse and complex habitat needed by most woodland creatures.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Monocultures, often planted for commercial purposes or ease of management, lack the biodiversity of natural forests.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] These single-species forests provide limited food sources, shelter, and nesting sites for a wide range of wildlife, and in purely coniferous forests low levels of light may reach the forest floor reducing habitat and variety of plant life.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Many woodland creatures, such as birds, mammals, and insects, rely on a variety of tree species and plant life for survival, and the uniformity of monocultures does not support these varied ecological needs.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] As a result, such reforestation or afforestation efforts may unintentionally create environments that are unsuitable for the very species they aim to protect, thus undermining broader conservation goals.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] The Great Green Wall of Africa is a ~5,000 mile forest being planted across the continent to stop the spread of the Sahara Desert to the south.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] In Adelaide, South Australia (a city of 1.3 million as of June 2016), Premier Mike Rann (2002 to 2011) launched an urban forest initiative in 2003 to plant 3 million native trees and shrubs by 2014 on 300 project sites across the metro area.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Thousands of Adelaide citizens participated in community planting days on sites including parks, reserves, transport corridors, schools, water courses and coastline.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Only native trees were planted to ensure genetic integrity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Rann said the project aimed to beautify and cool the city and make it more livable, improve air and water quality, and reduce Adelaide's greenhouse gas emissions by 600,000 tonnes of CO2 per year.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] In 2003, the government of Canada created a four-year project called the Forest 2020 Plantation Development and Assessment Initiative, which involved planting 6000 ha of fast-growing forests on non-forested lands countrywide.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] These plantations were used to analyze how afforestation can help to increase carbon sequestration and mitigate greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions while also considering the economic and investment attractiveness of afforestation.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] On 14 December 2020, Canada's Minister of Natural Resources Seamus O'Regan announced the federal government's investment of $3.16 billion to plant two billion trees over the next 10 years.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] This plan aims to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by an estimated 12 megatonnes by 2050.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] China had the highest afforestation rate of any country or region in the world, with 4.77 million hectares (47,000 square kilometers) of afforestation in 2008.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] According to the 2021 government work report, forest coverage will reach 24 percent based on the main targets and tasks for the 14th Five-Year Plan period.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] A law in China from 1981 requires that every school student over the age of 11 plants at least one tree per year.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] From 2011 to 2016, the city Dongying in Shandong province forested over 13,800 hectares of saline soil through the Shandong Ecological Afforestation Project, which was launched with support from the World Bank.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] In 2017, the Saihanba Afforestation Community won the UN Champions of the Earth Award in the Inspiration and Action category for "transforming degraded land into a lush paradise".
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] The successful afforestation of the Loess Plateau involved collaborative efforts by international and domestic professionals alongside villagers.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Through this initiative, millions of villagers across four of China's poorest provinces were able to improve farming practices and increase incomes and employment, alleviating poverty.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] In addition, the careful selection of trees ensured a healthy, self-sustainable ecosystem between tree and soil which facilitated a net carbon sink.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] The Loess Plateau, although successful, was costly, reaching almost US$500 million.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] This contrasts with more recent initiatives where the results have not been as favorable.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] In an attempt to make afforestation both low-cost and less time-consuming, China shifted towards monoculture of mostly red pine trees.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] However, this did not adequately take into consideration environmental structure and led to increased soil erosion, desertification, sand/dust storms and short-lived trees.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] This has reduced China's environmental sustainability index (ESI) to one of the lowest in the world.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Regarding the effects of afforestation on long-term carbon stocks and carbon sequestration these decrease when trees are less than 5 years old and increase quickly thereafter.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] This means trees from monoculture planting that do not survive never reach full potential for carbon sequestration to offset China's carbon output.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Overall, there is a possibility for afforestation to balance carbon levels and aid carbon neutrality, but several challenges still remain which hinder an all encompassing effort.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] The Chinese government requires mining companies to restore the environment around exhausted mines by refilling excavated pits and planting crops or trees.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Many mining companies use these recovered mines for ecotourism business.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Europe deforested more than half of its forested areas over the last 6000 years.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] The European Union (EU) has paid farmers for afforestation since 1990, offering grants to turn farmland into forest and payments for the management of forest.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] As part of the Green Deal, the EU program "3 Billion Tree Planting Pledge by 2030" provides direction on afforestation of previous farmland in addition to reforestation.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] According to Food and Agriculture Organization statistics, Spain had the third fastest afforestation rate in Europe in the 1990–2005 period, after Iceland and Ireland.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] In those years, a total of 44,360 square kilometers were afforested, and the total forest cover rose from 13.5 to 17.9 million hectares.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] In 1990, forests covered 26.6% of the Spanish territory.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] As of 2007, that figure had risen to 36.6%.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Spain today has the fifth largest forest area in the European Union.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] As of 2023 the total forest and tree cover in India was 22%.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] The forests of India are grouped into 5 major categories and 16 types based on biophysical criteria.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] 38% of the forest is categorized as subtropical dry deciduous and 30% as tropical moist deciduous and other smaller groups.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] In 2016 the Indian government passed the CAMPA (Compensatory Afforestation Fund Management and Planning Authority) law, allowing about 40 thousand crores rupees (almost $6 Billion) to go to Indian states for planting trees.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] In 2016 the Maharashtra government planted almost 20,000,000 saplings and pledged to plant another 30,000,000 the following year.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] In 2019, 220 million trees were planted in a single day in the Indian state of Uttar Pradesh.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] With wood production as a main objective, monocultures of Aleppo pine were vigorously planted between 1948 and the 1970s.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Following a massive collapse of this species in the 1990s, due to attacks by the insect pine blast scale, the Aleppo pine was gradually replaced by Pinus brutia.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Since the 1990s there has been a trend towards more ecological approaches planting mixed forests combining pines with broadleaf Mediterranean species e.g. oak, pistachio, carob, olive, arbutus and buckthorn.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] About 250 million trees have been planted through the JNF across Israel since 1990.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Tree coverage increased from 2% in 1948 to over 8% at present.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] The Japanese temperate rainforest is well sustained and maintains a high biodiversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] One method that has been utilized in maintaining the health of forests in Japan has been afforestation.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] The Japanese government and private businesses have set up multiple projects to plant native tree species in open areas scattered throughout the country.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] This practice has resulted in shifts in forest structure and a healthy temperate rainforest that maintains a high biodiversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] In January 2013, the UK government set a target of 12% woodland cover in England by 2060, up from the then 10%.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] In Wales the National Assembly for Wales has set a target of 19% woodland cover, up from 15%.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Government-backed initiatives such as the Woodland Carbon Code are intended to support this objective by encouraging corporations and landowners to create new woodland to offset their carbon emissions.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Charitable groups such as Trees for Life (Scotland) contribute to afforestation and reforestation efforts in the UK.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Afforestation efforts in Scotland have provided an increase in woodland expansion.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] By the 20th century mark, Scotland had diminished woodland coverage to 5% of Scotland's land area.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] However, by the early 21st century, afforestation efforts have increased woodland coverage to 17%.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] The Scottish government released their Draft Climate Change Plan in January 2017.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] The 2017 draft plan has increased the targeted woodland coverage to 21% by 2032 and increases the afforestation rate to 15,000 hectares per year.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] In the 1800s people moving westward in the US encountered the Great Plains – land with fertile soil, a growing population and a demand for timber but with few trees to supply it.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] So tree planting was encouraged along homesteads.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Arbor Day was founded in 1872 by Julius Sterling Morton in Nebraska City.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] By the 1930s the Dust Bowl environmental disaster signified a reason for adding significant new tree cover.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/afforestation] Public works programs under the New Deal saw the planting of 18,000 miles of windbreaks stretching from North Dakota to Texas to fight soil erosion (see Great Plains Shelterbelt).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Arabian oryx (*Oryx leucoryx*), also called the white oryx, was extinct in the wild as of 1972, but was reintroduced to the wild starting in 1982.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The initial reintroduction was primarily from two herds: the "World Herd" originally started at the Phoenix Zoo in 1963 from only nine oryx and the Saudi Arabian herd started in 1986 from private collections and some "World Herd" stock by the Saudi National Wildlife Research Center (NWRC).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2009, there have been reintroductions in Oman, Saudi Arabia, Israel, the United Arab Emirates, and Jordan, and as of 2013 the IUCN Red List classifies the species as vulnerable.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Arabian oryx was known to be in decline since the early 1900s in the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] By the 1930, there were two separate populations isolated from each other.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Talbot reported that Arabian oryx appeared to be extinct in its former range along the southern edge of Ar-Rub' al-Khali.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] He believed that any oryx still existing would be exterminated within the next few years and recommended that a captive breeding program be started to save the species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Michael Crouch, then Assistant Adviser in the Eastern Aden Protectorate, drew attention to the fact that each spring, small groups of oryx still emerged onto the gravel plains in the northeast corner of the Protectorate, where he thought a capture attempt would be possible.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The initial plan of the Fauna and Flora Preservation Society was to establish a herd in Kenya where another species of oryx already lived and flourished.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Kenyan plan was dropped because of an outbreak of hoof-and-mouth disease, and the oryx destined for Kenya were shipped to the Phoenix Zoo instead.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] There were originally four individuals captured and seven donated for this project.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The four were captured in Aden (now Yemen) near the border of Oman by an expedition led by the late Major Ian Grimwood, then chief game warden of Kenya, with help from Manahil and Mahra tribesmen.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] One male from this group later died of capture stress.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The seven donated oryx were: one from the London Zoo, two from Sheikh Jaber Abdullah al-Sabah, and two pairs from the collection of King Saud bin Abdul Aziz.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Five Arabian oryx were delivered to the Phoenix Zoo in 1963 (four in June and one in September).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] A baby was born to the herd in October 1963 from a conception en route and another was born in spring 1964, bringing the starting population of the Phoenix Zoo herd to seven.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The four oryx donated by King Saud arrived at the Phoenix Zoo in July 1964, bringing the population of the "World Herd" to 11.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The breeding program at the Phoenix Zoo was very successful, and the zoo celebrated its 225th Arabian oryx birth in 2002.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] From Phoenix, individuals were sent to other zoos and parks (including the San Diego Wild Animal Park) to start their herds.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Most of the Arabian oryx in the wild today have ancestors from the Phoenix Zoo.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Reintroductions started in 1982 in Oman.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2009 there have been reintroductions in Oman, Saudi Arabia, Israel, the United Arab Emirates, and Jordan.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] At this time, populations in the United Arab Emirates and Jordan are still not considered in the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) Red List wild oryx count.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The population in Oman is still receiving supplementary forage, and the introduction into Jordan was after the last update of the Red List.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] By 1980, the number of Arabian oryx in captivity had increased to the point that reintroduction to Oman was attempted from the San Diego Wild Animal Park to Jaaluni in the Jiddat al-Harasis.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The oryx were initially kept in large pens outdoors, but were released to the wild on January 31, 1982, in the Omani Central Desert and Coastal Hills.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] These oryx became the core of the Oman herd in the wild, though there were several other releases of captive bred animals over the next two decades.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The area of their release became the Arabian Oryx Sanctuary.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] On June 28, 2007, Oman's Arabian Oryx Sanctuary was the first site to be removed from the UNESCO World Heritage List.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] UNESCO cited the Omani government's decision to open 90% of the site to oil prospecting as the main reason for this decision.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Arabian oryx population on the site has been reduced from 450 oryx in 1996 to only 65 in 2007, mostly due to poaching and illegal live capture.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] There are now fewer than four breeding pairs left on the site.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Organized captive breeding of the Arabian oryx in Saudi Arabia began in April 1986, when 57 oryx from the farm of the late King Khalid bin Abdul Aziz in King Khalid Wildlife Research Center were brought to the National Wildlife Research Center (NWRC) near At-Ta'if.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Between the initial 1986 founding and 1996, 33 additional oryx (including some from the "World Herd") have been introduced to the founder generation of Arabian oryx at the NWRC.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Since 1996, all additions to the population have been through births.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Due to an outbreak of *Mycobacterium bovis* (bovine tuberculosis) in the founder generation, a "buffer generation" was introduced in the herd.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Since then, calves produced by the founder herd are removed from their dam immediately after birth and hand-reared.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] These hand-reared second generation oryx are regularly tested for tuberculosis and a variety of other pathogenic agents, and join the breeding nucleus only when tests are consecutively negative.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] After breeding, they produce the third generation of oryx, which are tuberculosis free and mother-reared, and of which more than 80% are reintroduced into the wild.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Reintroduction of a wild population began in 1995 in the 'Uruq Bani Ma'arid Protected Area.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The reserve covers about 12,000 km2 (4,600 sq mi) at the western edge of the Rubʿ al-Khali desert or "Empty Quarter".
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2009, the IUCN Red List estimates the oryx population on this reserve at 160 individuals.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] A free ranging herd was established in the newly created Mahazat as-Sayd Protected Area in 1989.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] This 2,244 km2 (866 sq mi) fenced reserve is home to reintroduced oryx, gazelle and the houbara bustard.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2009, the IUCN Red List estimates the oryx population on this reserve at about 800 individuals.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In Israel the reintroduction program was established in 1978 when four pairs of Arabian oryx were purchased.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] At this time the IUCN Redbook reported wild populations totaling 90–100 animals in three locations in Northern Arava and the Negev Desert.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2014 there are around 130 animals in the Aravah, and in 2013 they began to spread to the central Negev and the population keeps increasing.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In addition to the natural population increase, every year around six animals are released to the wild in Israel.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Israel is the only country in which the Arabian oryx was reintroduced where poaching prohibition can be enforced, and because of this the Israeli population grows annually.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Apart from the wild oryx population in Israel, there are a few dozen oryx in the Yotvata Hai-Bar Nature Reserve, a few breeding couples in the Jerusalem Biblical Zoo and a small herd in the Ramat Gan Safari.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The reintroduction of oryx in Israel is one of a few successful programs reintroducing animals into nature in Israel; others include the introduction of the Persian onager (a proxy for the extinct Syrian onager), and the very successful reintroduction of Persian fallow deer.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In the early 1960s, the late Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan directed the capture of two breeding pairs of the oryx for the nucleus of a captive-breeding program in Al Ain, which would lead to the formation of the city's zoo.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In 2007 the United Arab Emirates started releasing animals into Umm Al Zumul.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2009 there have been about 100 animals released.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As part of this initiative, a similar program is being developed to reintroduce this extinct species into its natural habitats in Yemen and Iraq.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Since March 1999, the Emirate of Abu Dhabi has been host to an inter-governmental body known as The Coordinating Committee for the Conservation of the Arabian Oryx, which oversees the coordination of conservation efforts for this species within the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In 2012, GSCAO carried out an Arabian Oryx Disease Survey which was funded by the Environment Agency – Abu Dhabi (EAD), in the range states.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Arabian oryx are periodically released in protected areas, such as the Qasr Al Sarab Protected Area.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2017, it is estimated that around 10,000 Arabian oryx, of which 5,000 are estimated to be in Abu Dhabi, are currently in the United Arab Emirates.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The reintroduction project for Jordan began when the Environment Agency of Abu Dhabi (EAD) and the Al Aqaba Special Economic Zone Authority signed a sponsorship agreement in April 2007.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Under this agreement, EAD is sponsoring the million three-year project which includes reintroduction of the Arabian oryx into the Wadi Rum Protected Area, rehabilitating the habitat, and helping local residents to improve their living standards.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Twenty oryx (12 males and 8 females) were released into the Wadi Rum Protected Area in July 2009.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In 1986, as a result of the reintroduction efforts, the IUCN re-listed the Arabian oryx from extinct in the wild to endangered.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] By 2009, the Arabian oryx was protected by law in all areas where it appears.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In June 2011, the Arabian oryx was re-listed as vulnerable by the IUCN Red List.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In 2016 the IUCN estimated there were more than 1000 Arabian oryx in the wild, with 6000–7000 held in captivity worldwide in zoos, preserves, and private collections.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Some of these are in large fenced enclosures (free-roaming), including those in Syria (Al Talila), Bahrain, Qatar, and UAE.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] This is the first time the IUCN has re-classified a species as vulnerable after it had been listed as extinct in the wild.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Arabian oryx is also listed in CITES Appendix I.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/assisted-natural-regeneration] The most effective way to implement ANR is very site-specific, and many nations provide guidebooks on how to select and maintain an ANR project.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/assisted-natural-regeneration] ANR is a common practice in many Asian countries.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/assisted-natural-regeneration] This method of protection has been used on *Imperata* grasslands in the Philippines for over three decades, as well as in China for more than five decades.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/assisted-natural-regeneration] According to the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO), China has since 1999 funded extensive ANR in an effort to prevent soil corrosion in particular.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/assisted-natural-regeneration] Also the FAO reports that ANR is a common practice in Thailand.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/assisted-natural-regeneration] ANR is gaining popularity as global climate change becomes a growing concern.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/assisted-natural-regeneration] ANR has typically been used most often in tropical forests, however, it is now being used to help restore forested areas across all ecosystem types.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/assisted-natural-regeneration] A wide variety of conditions are required to optimally implement ANR and ensure successful regeneration.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/assisted-natural-regeneration] One involves a sufficient density of naturally regenerated seedlings, though the specific density required is dependent on specific factors, such as, distribution, species composition, growth rates, soil fertility, etc.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/assisted-natural-regeneration] A density range of 200 to 800 seedlings per hectare has been suggested to ensure optimal regeneration.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/assisted-natural-regeneration] The availability of seed sources from nearby remnant forests is necessary to serve as seed inputs for colonization of vegetation.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/assisted-natural-regeneration] The control or removal of all disturbances (such as, grazing, fires, and logging) is also crucial.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/assisted-natural-regeneration] The practice of ANR has a wide range of benefits.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/assisted-natural-regeneration] ANR focuses on reducing ecological barriers in order to accelerate natural regeneration and growth, rather than the planting of seedlings.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/assisted-natural-regeneration] This allows for a low-cost method that removes the expenses associated with site preparation and planting/raising seedlings themselves, which can be appealing in large-scale restoration projects.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/assisted-natural-regeneration] Another benefit involves job opportunities.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/assisted-natural-regeneration] ANR requires high maintenance and can be labor-intensive, and involve methods of weeding, grass pressing, establishing and maintaining firebreaks, etc.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/assisted-natural-regeneration] This can ultimately help to create jobs and improve livelihoods in local and/or impoverished communities.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/assisted-natural-regeneration] However, if the forestation is not a positive change, for example, if the land is needed for food, the people of the community will be unlikely to get involved and produce successful ANR.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/assisted-natural-regeneration] Carbon sequestration, biodiversity enrichment and recovery are just a few environmental benefits ANR provides, which can help improve ecosystems and mitigate climate change.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/assisted-natural-regeneration] ANR focuses on native species and natural succession of existing vegetation, which ensures that plant communities and inhabiting wildlife are maintained and are not disturbed.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bear-conservation] Bears face serious threats on many fronts, most of which are due to human activity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bear-conservation] Whether indirect, as in human encroachment on their natural habitats due to crop cultivation, deforestation or timber harvest, or directly from their killing for protection of property or for unregulated or sport hunting, or for their use in primitive medicines and aphrodisiacs.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bear-conservation] In a paper presented at the International Bear Association’s Eighth International Conference on Bear Research and Management, Victoria, British Columbia, Canada, in 1989, Christopher Servheen, of the U.S.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bear-conservation] According to Servheen, bear conservation efforts vary from the intensive and highly organized management of the grizzly bear in the United States to little management in Asian countries.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bear-conservation] However, since 2004 the non-profit organization Free the Bears (FTB) has been working to rescue bears in Asia along with educating the local communities.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bear-conservation] They help combat the illegal wildlife trade of bears and often transport the rescues to world-class sanctuaries.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bear-conservation] This dedicated program is not only working to reduce illegal trade and capture of bears in the Asian area but other impoverished and dangerous parts of the world.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bear-conservation] Likewise, successful international co-operation in conservation and management is exemplified by the work done on the polar bear in the Arctic.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bear-conservation] Several other species also need international cooperation to if they are to survive.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bear-conservation] However, even species of "least concern" such as the brown bear are at risk of extirpation in certain countries or regions beyond their range in North America, parts of Europe, and the former Soviet Union.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bear-conservation] The process of decline and/or extinction of the brown bear in Europe is well documented.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bear-conservation] Starting with their extinction in Denmark around 3000 BC, in Great Britain during the 10th century, in eastern Germany in 1770, in Bavaria in 1836, in Switzerland in 1904, and in the French Alps in 1937.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bear-conservation] Although the inclusion of the brown bear as of least concern on the 2006 IUCN Red List of Threatened Species refers to their global population, the fact is that local populations are increasingly becoming scarcer.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bear-conservation] Such regional variations are most obvious in Spain where the only remaining bear, the Cantabrian brown bear is under threat.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bear-conservation] Spain’s ministry of the environment, in its *Catálogo Nacional de Especies Amenazadas* lists the brown bear as in danger of extinction in Spain.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bear-conservation] According to an article published December 2007 in the Spanish national daily *El País*, eight brown bears had been killed, either by poisoned bait or illegal hunting, in the Cantabrian Mountains since 2000.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bear-conservation] The Cantabrian brown bear population is currently (2007) estimated at around 170, divided between the 140 in the western section and 25-30 in the eastern.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bear-conservation] Leading Spanish experts have warned that the bear population will not be viable until there are "several hundred".
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bear-conservation] One way forward is to reverse the fragmentation of the bears' habitat by creating "corridors".
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bear-conservation] However, their viability is compromised by the regional authorities' keenness to allow construction of a ski resort at San Glorio, a project which has met strong opposition from many sectors, as well as that of the central government.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Since life began on Earth, six major mass extinctions and several minor events have led to large and sudden drops in biodiversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The Phanerozoic aeon (the last 540 million years) marked a rapid growth in biodiversity via the Cambrian explosion.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] In this period, the majority of multicellular phyla first appeared.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The next 400 million years included repeated, massive biodiversity losses.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Those events have been classified as mass extinction events.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] In the Carboniferous, rainforest collapse may have led to a great loss of plant and animal life.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The Permian–Triassic extinction event, 251 million years ago, was the worst; vertebrate recovery took 30 million years.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Human activities have led to an ongoing biodiversity loss and an accompanying loss of genetic diversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] This process is often referred to as Holocene extinction, or the *sixth mass extinction*.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] For example, it was estimated in 2007 that up to 30% of all species will be extinct by 2050.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Destroying habitats for farming is a key reason why biodiversity is decreasing today.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] This can be seen for example in the effects of climate change on biomes.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] This anthropogenic extinction may have started toward the end of the Pleistocene, as some studies suggest that the megafaunal extinction event that took place around the end of the last ice age partly resulted from overhunting.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Biologists most often define *biodiversity* as the "totality of genes, species and ecosystems of a region".
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] (2011), there are approximately 8.7 million terrestrial species and 2.2 million oceanic species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The authors note that these estimates are strongest for eukaryotic organisms and likely represent the lower bound of prokaryotic diversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Since the rate of extinction has increased, many extant species may become extinct before they are described.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Not surprisingly, in the Animalia the most studied groups are birds and mammals, whereas fishes and arthropods are the least studied animal groups.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] During the last century, decreases in biodiversity have been increasingly observed.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] It was estimated in 2007 that up to 30% of all species will be extinct by 2050.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Of these, about one eighth of known plant species are threatened with extinction.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Estimates reach as high as 140,000 species per year (based on Species-area theory).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] This figure indicates unsustainable ecological practices, because few species emerge each year.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The rate of species loss is greater now than at any time in human history, with extinctions occurring at rates hundreds of times higher than background extinction rates. and expected to still grow in the upcoming years.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] As of 2012, some studies suggest that 25% of all mammal species could be extinct in 20 years.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] According to a 2016 study by the World Wildlife Fund, population abundance among 3,706 monitored vertebrate species is exhibiting a persistent downward trend.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The *Living Planet Report 2014* claims that "the number of mammals, birds, reptiles, amphibians, and fish across the globe is, on average, about half the size it was 40 years ago".
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Of that number, 39% accounts for the terrestrial wildlife gone, 39% for the marine wildlife gone and 76% for the freshwater wildlife gone.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity took the biggest hit in Latin America, plummeting 83 percent.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] High-income countries showed a 10% increase in biodiversity, which was canceled out by a loss in low-income countries.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] This is despite the fact that high-income countries use five times the ecological resources of low-income countries, which was explained as a result of a process whereby wealthy nations are outsourcing resource depletion to poorer nations, which are suffering the greatest ecosystem losses.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] A 2017 study published in *PLOS One* found that the biomass of insect life in Germany had declined by three-quarters in the last 25 years.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Dave Goulson of Sussex University stated that their study suggested that humans "appear to be making vast tracts of land inhospitable to most forms of life, and are currently on course for ecological Armageddon.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] In 2020 the World Wildlife Fund published a report saying that "biodiversity is being destroyed at a rate unprecedented in human history".
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The report claims that 68% of the population of the examined species were destroyed in the years 1970 – 2016.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Of 70,000 monitored species, around 48% are experiencing population declines from human activity (in 2023), whereas only 3% have increasing populations.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Rates of decline in biodiversity in the current sixth mass extinction match or exceed rates of loss in the five previous mass extinction events in the fossil record.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity loss is in fact "one of the most critical manifestations of the Anthropocene" (since around the 1950s); the continued decline of biodiversity constitutes "an unprecedented threat" to the continued existence of human civilization.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The reduction is caused primarily by human impacts, particularly habitat destruction.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Since the Stone Age, species loss has accelerated above the average basal rate, driven by human activity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Estimates of species losses are at a rate 100–10,000 times as fast as is typical in the fossil record.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Loss of biodiversity results in the loss of natural capital that supplies ecosystem goods and services.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Species today are being wiped out at a rate 100 to 1,000 times higher than baseline, and the rate of extinctions is increasing.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] This process destroys the resilience and adaptability of life on Earth.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] In 2006, many species were formally classified as rare or endangered or threatened; moreover, scientists have estimated that millions more species are at risk which have not been formally recognized.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] About 40 percent of the 40,177 species assessed using the IUCN Red List criteria are now listed as threatened with extinction—a total of 16,119.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] As of late 2022 9251 species were considered part of the IUCN's critically endangered.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Numerous scientists and the IPBES *Global Assessment Report on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services* assert that human population growth and overconsumption are the primary factors in this decline.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] However, other scientists have criticized this finding and say that loss of habitat caused by "the growth of commodities for export" is the main driver.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] A 2025 study found that human activities are responsible for biodiversity loss across all species and ecosystems.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Climate change is an important driver of global biodiversity loss because of its impacts on ecosystems.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] At the same time, biodiversity and climate are closely interconnected, as biodiversity influences the mitigation and adaptation potential of ecosystems.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] For more information on these interactions, see the 'Regulating services' section below.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Other studies, however, have pointed out that habitat destruction for the expansion of agriculture and the overexploitation of wildlife are the more significant drivers of contemporary biodiversity loss, not climate change.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is not evenly distributed, rather it varies greatly across the globe as well as within regions and seasons.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Among other factors, the diversity of all living things (biota) depends on temperature, precipitation, altitude, soils, geography and the interactions between other species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The study of the spatial distribution of organisms, species and ecosystems, is the science of biogeography.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Diversity consistently measures higher in the tropics and in other localized regions such as the Cape Floristic Region and lower in polar regions generally.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Rain forests that have had wet climates for a long time, such as Yasuní National Park in Ecuador, have particularly high biodiversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] There is local biodiversity, which directly impacts daily life, affecting the availability of fresh water, food choices, and fuel sources for humans.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Regional biodiversity includes habitats and ecosystems that synergizes and either overlaps or differs on a regional scale.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] National biodiversity within a country determines the ability for a country to thrive according to its habitats and ecosystems on a national scale.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Also, within a country, endangered species are initially supported on a national level then internationally.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Ecotourism may be utilized to support the economy and encourages tourists to continue to visit and support species and ecosystems they visit, while they enjoy the available amenities provided.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] International biodiversity impacts global livelihood, food systems, and health.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Problematic pollution, over consumption, and climate change can devastate international biodiversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Nature-based solutions are a critical tool for a global resolution.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Many species are in danger of becoming extinct and need world leaders to be proactive with the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Terrestrial biodiversity is thought to be up to 25 times greater than ocean biodiversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Forests harbour most of Earth's terrestrial biodiversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The conservation of the world's biodiversity is thus utterly dependent on the way in which we interact with and use the world's forests.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] A new method used in 2011, put the total number of species on Earth at 8.7 million, of which 2.1 million were estimated to live in the ocean.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] However, this estimate seems to under-represent the diversity of microorganisms.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Forests provide habitats for 80 percent of amphibian species, 75 percent of bird species and 68 percent of mammal species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] About 60 percent of all vascular plants are found in tropical forests.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Mangroves provide breeding grounds and nurseries for numerous species of fish and shellfish and help trap sediments that might otherwise adversely affect seagrass beds and coral reefs, which are habitats for many more marine species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Forests span around 4 billion acres (nearly a third of the Earth's land mass) and are home to approximately 80% of the world's biodiversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] About 1 billion hectares are covered by primary forests.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Over 700 million hectares of the world's woods are officially protected.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The biodiversity of forests varies considerably according to factors such as forest type, geography, climate and soils – in addition to human use.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Areas with dense human populations and intense agricultural land use, such as Europe, parts of Bangladesh, China, India and North America, are less intact in terms of their biodiversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Northern Africa, southern Australia, coastal Brazil, Madagascar and South Africa, are also identified as areas with striking losses in biodiversity intactness.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] European forests in EU and non-EU nations comprise more than 30% of Europe's land mass (around 227 million hectares), representing an almost 10% growth since 1990.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Generally, there is an increase in biodiversity from the poles to the tropics.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Thus localities at lower latitudes have more species than localities at higher latitudes.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] This is often referred to as the latitudinal gradient in species diversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Several ecological factors may contribute to the gradient, but the ultimate factor behind many of them is the greater mean temperature at the equator compared to that at the poles.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Even though terrestrial biodiversity declines from the equator to the poles, some studies claim that this characteristic is unverified in aquatic ecosystems, especially in marine ecosystems.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The latitudinal distribution of parasites does not appear to follow this rule.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Also, in terrestrial ecosystems the soil bacterial diversity has been shown to be highest in temperate climatic zones, and has been attributed to carbon inputs and habitat connectivity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] In 2016, an alternative hypothesis ("the fractal biodiversity") was proposed to explain the biodiversity latitudinal gradient.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] In this study, the species pool size and the fractal nature of ecosystems were combined to clarify some general patterns of this gradient.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] This hypothesis considers temperature, moisture, and net primary production (NPP) as the main variables of an ecosystem niche and as the axis of the ecological hypervolume.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] In this way, it is possible to build fractal hyper volumes, whose fractal dimension rises to three moving towards the equator.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] A biodiversity hotspot is a region with a high level of endemic species that have experienced great habitat loss.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The term hotspot was introduced in 1988 by Norman Myers.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] While hotspots are spread all over the world, the majority are forest areas and most are located in the tropics.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Brazil's Atlantic Forest is considered one such hotspot, containing roughly 20,000 plant species, 1,350 vertebrates and millions of insects, about half of which occur nowhere else.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The island of Madagascar and India are also particularly notable.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Colombia is characterized by high biodiversity, with the highest rate of species by area unit worldwide and it has the largest number of endemics (species that are not found naturally anywhere else) of any country.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] About 10% of the species of the Earth can be found in Colombia, including over 1,900 species of bird, more than in Europe and North America combined, Colombia has 10% of the world's mammals species, 14% of the amphibian species and 18% of the bird species of the world.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Madagascar dry deciduous forests and lowland rainforests possess a high ratio of endemism.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Since the island separated from mainland Africa 66 million years ago, many species and ecosystems have evolved independently.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Indonesia's 17,000 islands cover 735,355 square miles (1,904,560 km2) and contain 10% of the world's flowering plants, 12% of mammals and 17% of reptiles, amphibians and birds—along with nearly 240 million people.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Many regions of high biodiversity and/or endemism arise from specialized habitats which require unusual adaptations, for example, alpine environments in high mountains, or Northern European peat bogs.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Accurately measuring differences in biodiversity can be difficult.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Selection bias amongst researchers may contribute to biased empirical research for modern estimates of biodiversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is the result of 3.5 billion years of evolution.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The origin of life has not been established by science, however, some evidence suggests that life may already have been well-established only a few hundred million years after the formation of the Earth.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Until approximately 2.5 billion years ago, all life consisted of microorganisms – archaea, bacteria, and single-celled protozoans and protists.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity grew fast during the Phanerozoic (the last 540 million years), especially during the so-called Cambrian explosion—a period during which nearly every phylum of multicellular organisms first appeared.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] However, recent studies suggest that this diversification had started earlier, at least in the Ediacaran, and that it continued in the Ordovician.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Over the next 400 million years or so, invertebrate diversity showed little overall trend and vertebrate diversity shows an overall exponential trend.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] This dramatic rise in diversity was marked by periodic, massive losses of diversity classified as mass extinction events.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The worst was the Permian-Triassic extinction event, 251 million years ago.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Vertebrates took 30 million years to recover from this event.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The most recent major mass extinction event, the Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event, occurred 66 million years ago.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] This period has attracted more attention than others because it resulted in the extinction of the non-avian dinosaurs, which were represented by many lineages at the end of the Maastrichtian, just before that extinction event.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] However, many other taxa were affected by this crisis, which affected even marine taxa, such as ammonites, which also became extinct around that time.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The biodiversity of the past is called Paleobiodiversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The fossil record suggests that the last few million years featured the greatest biodiversity in history.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] However, not all scientists support this view, since there is uncertainty as to how strongly the fossil record is biased by the greater availability and preservation of recent geologic sections.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Some scientists believe that corrected for sampling artifacts, modern biodiversity may not be much different from biodiversity 300 million years ago, whereas others consider the fossil record reasonably reflective of the diversification of life.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Estimates of the present global macroscopic species diversity vary from 2 million to 100 million, with a best estimate of somewhere near 9 million, the vast majority arthropods.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Diversity appears to increase continually in the absence of natural selection.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The existence of a *global carrying capacity*, limiting the amount of life that can live at once, is debated, as is the question of whether such a limit would also cap the number of species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] While records of life in the sea show a logistic pattern of growth, life on land (insects, plants and tetrapods) shows an exponential rise in diversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] It also appears that the diversity continues to increase over time, especially after mass extinctions.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] On the other hand, changes through the Phanerozoic correlate much better with the hyperbolic model (widely used in population biology, demography and macrosociology, as well as fossil biodiversity) than with exponential and logistic models.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The latter models imply that changes in diversity are guided by a first-order positive feedback (more ancestors, more descendants) and/or a negative feedback arising from resource limitation.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Hyperbolic model implies a second-order positive feedback.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Differences in the strength of the second-order feedback due to different intensities of interspecific competition might explain the faster rediversification of ammonoids in comparison to bivalves after the end-Permian extinction.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The hyperbolic pattern of the world population growth arises from a second-order positive feedback between the population size and the rate of technological growth.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The hyperbolic character of biodiversity growth can be similarly accounted for by a feedback between diversity and community structure complexity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The similarity between the curves of biodiversity and human population probably comes from the fact that both are derived from the interference of the hyperbolic trend with cyclical and stochastic dynamics.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Most biologists agree however that the period since human emergence is part of a new mass extinction, named the Holocene extinction event, caused primarily by the impact humans are having on the environment.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] It has been argued that the present rate of extinction is sufficient to eliminate most species on the planet Earth within 100 years.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] New species are regularly discovered (on average between 5–10,000 new species each year, most of them insects) and many, though discovered, are not yet classified (estimates are that nearly 90% of all arthropods are not yet classified).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Most of the terrestrial diversity is found in tropical forests and in general, the land has more species than the ocean; some 8.7 million species may exist on Earth, of which some 2.1 million live in the ocean.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] It is estimated that 5 to 50 billion species have existed on the planet.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Assuming that there may be a maximum of about 50 million species currently alive, it stands to reason that greater than 99% of the planet's species went extinct prior to the evolution of humans.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Estimates on the number of Earth's current species range from 10 million to 14 million, of which about 1.2 million have been documented and over 86% have not yet been described.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] However, a May 2016 scientific report estimates that 1 trillion species are currently on Earth, with only one-thousandth of one percent described.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The total amount of related DNA base pairs on Earth is estimated at 5.0 × 1037 and weighs 50 billion tonnes.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] In comparison, the total mass of the biosphere has been estimated to be as much as four trillion tons of carbon.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] In July 2016, scientists reported identifying a set of 355 genes from the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all organisms living on Earth.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The age of Earth is about 4.54 billion years.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The earliest undisputed evidence of life dates at least from 3.7 billion years ago, during the Eoarchean era after a geological crust started to solidify following the earlier molten Hadean eon.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] There are microbial mat fossils found in 3.48 billion-year-old sandstone discovered in Western Australia.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Other early physical evidence of a biogenic substance is graphite in 3.7 billion-year-old meta-sedimentary rocks discovered in Western Greenland.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] More recently, in 2015, "remains of biotic life" were found in 4.1 billion-year-old rocks in Western Australia.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] There have been many claims about biodiversity's effect on the ecosystem services, especially *provisioning* and *regulating services*.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Some of those claims have been validated, some are incorrect and some lack enough evidence to draw definitive conclusions.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Experiments with controlled environments have shown that humans cannot easily build ecosystems to support human needs; for example insect pollination cannot be mimicked, though there have been attempts to create artificial pollinators using unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The economic activity of pollination alone represented between $2.1–14.6 billion in 2003.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Other sources have reported somewhat conflicting results and in 1997 Robert Costanza and his colleagues reported the estimated global value of ecosystem services (not captured in traditional markets) at an average of $33 trillion annually.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity plays a role in multiple ecological regulating services that strengthen the stability, functioning and adaptability of ecosystems.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] For example, plant species richness can increase functional diversity in many ecosystems.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Different plant organisms living together can perform complementary roles such as nutrient cycling and water regulation, which can contribute to the stabilisation of ecosystem processes under climate stress, a mechanism known as niche complementarity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] This could include enhanced transpiration and soil moisture regulation, as more efficient water use can be promoted by the variety of different leaf traits and root depths, which in turn can reduce drought stress and mitigate heat impact.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Climate change is also associated with higher pathogen pressure on terrestrial and marine ecosystems.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] In many ecosystems higher biodiversity could contribute to greater resilience to pests and diseases, as diversity in host traits and interactions can interrupt disease spread and reduce the severity of the outbreak.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] In coastal ecosystems genetic diversity within a species can further enhance its adaptive capacity by providing a range of traits that support populations to persist under changing temperature and precipitation regimes.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Furthermore, in terrestrial ecosystems higher biodiversity can promote mutualistic interactions (like pollination or mycorrhizal networks), which can enhance nutrient uptake and support overall productivity and resilience.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The other category of agricultural diversity is called interspecific diversity and refers to the number and types of different species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Agricultural diversity can also be divided by whether it is 'planned' diversity or 'associated' diversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] This is a functional classification that we impose and not an intrinsic feature of life or diversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Associated biodiversity can be damaging or beneficial.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The beneficial associated biodiversity include for instance wild pollinators such as wild bees and syrphid flies that pollinate crops and natural enemies and antagonists to pests and pathogens.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Beneficial associated biodiversity occurs abundantly in crop fields and provide multiple ecosystem services such as pest control, nutrient cycling and pollination that support crop production.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Although about 80 percent of humans' food supply comes from just 20 kinds of plants, humans use at least 40,000 species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Earth's surviving biodiversity provides resources for increasing the range of food and other products suitable for human use, although the present extinction rate shrinks that potential.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity's relevance to human health is becoming an international political issue, as scientific evidence builds on the global health implications of biodiversity loss.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Some of the health issues influenced by biodiversity include dietary health and nutrition security, infectious disease, medical science and medicinal resources, social and psychological health.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is also known to have an important role in reducing disaster risk, including rising sea levels.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] For example, wetland ecosystems along coastal communities serve as excellent water filtration systems, storage, and ultimately create a buffer region between the ocean and mainland neighborhoods in order to prevent water reaching these communities under climate change pressures or storm surges.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Other examples of diverse species or organisms are present around the world, offering their resourceful utilities to provide protection of human survival.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity provides critical support for drug discovery and the availability of medicinal resources.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Only a tiny fraction of wild species has been investigated for medical potential.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] This process of bioprospecting can increase biodiversity loss, as well as violating the laws of the communities and states from which the resources are taken.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] According to the Boston Consulting Group, in 2021, the economic value that biodiversity has on society comes down to four definable terms: regulation, culture, habitat, and provisioning.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] To sum these up in a relatively short manner, biodiversity helps maintain habitat and animal functions that provide considerable amounts of resources that benefit the economy.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity's economic resources are worth at around $150 trillion annually which is roughly twice the world's GDP.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The loss of biodiversity is actually harming the GDP of the world by costing an estimated $5 trillion annually.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Business supply chains rely heavily on ecosystems remaining relatively maintained and nurtured.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] A disruption to these supply chains would negatively impact many businesses that would end up costing them more than what they are gaining.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Philosophically it could be argued that biodiversity has intrinsic aesthetic and spiritual value to mankind *in and of itself*.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] This idea can be used as a counterweight to the notion that tropical forests and other ecological realms are only worthy of conservation because of the services they provide.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity also affords many non-material benefits including spiritual and aesthetic values, knowledge systems and education.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] A variety of objective means exist to empirically measure biodiversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Each measure relates to a particular use of the data, and is likely to be associated with the variety of genes.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is commonly measured in terms of taxonomic richness of a geographic area over a time interval.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] In order to calculate biodiversity, species evenness, species richness, and species diversity are to be obtained first.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] *Species evenness* is the relative number of individuals of each species in a given area.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] *Species richness* is the number of species present in a given area.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] *Species diversity* is the relationship between species evenness and species richness.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] There are many ways to measure biodiversity within a given ecosystem.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] However, the two most popular are Shannon-Weaver diversity index, commonly referred to as Shannon diversity index, and the other is Simpsons diversity index.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Although many scientists prefer to use Shannon's diversity index simply because it takes into account species richness.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Less than 1% of all species that have been described have been studied beyond noting their existence.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The vast majority of Earth's species are microbial.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Contemporary biodiversity physics is "firmly fixated on the visible [macroscopic] world".
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] For example, microbial life is metabolically and environmentally more diverse than multicellular life (see e.g., extremophile).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] "On the tree of life, based on analyses of small-subunit ribosomal RNA, visible life consists of barely noticeable twigs.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The inverse relationship of size and population recurs higher on the evolutionary ladder—to a first approximation, all multicellular species on Earth are insects".
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Insect extinction rates are high—supporting the Holocene extinction hypothesis.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity naturally varies due to seasonal shifts.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Spring's arrival enhances biodiversity as numerous species breed and feed, while winter's onset temporarily reduces it as some insects perish and migrating animals leave.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Additionally, the seasonal fluctuation in plant and invertebrate populations influences biodiversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Barriers such as large rivers, seas, oceans, mountains and deserts encourage diversity by enabling independent evolution on either side of the barrier, via the process of allopatric speciation.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The term invasive species is applied to species that breach the natural barriers that would normally keep them constrained.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Without barriers, such species occupy new territory, often supplanting native species by occupying their niches, or by using resources that would normally sustain native species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Species are increasingly being moved by humans (on purpose and accidentally).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Some studies say that diverse ecosystems are more resilient and resist invasive plants and animals.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Many studies cite effects of invasive species on natives, but not extinctions.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Invasive species seem to increase local (alpha diversity) diversity, which decreases turnover of diversity (beta diversity).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Overall gamma diversity may be lowered because species are going extinct because of other causes, but even some of the most insidious invaders (e.g.: Dutch elm disease, emerald ash borer, chestnut blight in North America) have not caused their host species to become extinct.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Extirpation, population decline and homogenization of regional biodiversity are much more common.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Human activities have frequently been the cause of invasive species circumventing their barriers, by introducing them for food and other purposes.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Human activities therefore allow species to migrate to new areas (and thus become invasive) occurred on time scales much shorter than historically have been required for a species to extend its range.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] At present, several countries have already imported so many exotic species, particularly agricultural and ornamental plants, that their indigenous fauna/flora may be outnumbered.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] For example, the introduction of kudzu from Southeast Asia to Canada and the United States has threatened biodiversity in certain areas.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Another example are pines, which have invaded forests, shrublands and grasslands in the southern hemisphere.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Endemic species can be threatened with extinction through the process of genetic pollution, i.e. uncontrolled hybridization, introgression and genetic swamping.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Genetic pollution leads to homogenization or replacement of local genomes as a result of either a numerical and/or fitness advantage of an introduced species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Hybridization and introgression are side-effects of introduction and invasion.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] These phenomena can be especially detrimental to rare species that come into contact with more abundant ones.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The abundant species can interbreed with the rare species, swamping its gene pool.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] This problem is not always apparent from morphological (outward appearance) observations alone.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Some degree of gene flow is normal adaptation and not all gene and genotype constellations can be preserved.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] However, hybridization with or without introgression may, nevertheless, threaten a rare species' existence.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Conservation biology matured in the mid-20th century as ecologists, naturalists and other scientists began to research and address issues pertaining to global biodiversity declines.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] The conservation ethic advocates management of natural resources for the purpose of sustaining biodiversity in species, ecosystems, the evolutionary process and human culture and society.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Conservation biology is reforming around strategic plans to protect biodiversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Preserving global biodiversity is a priority in strategic conservation plans that are designed to engage public policy and concerns affecting local, regional and global scales of communities, ecosystems and cultures.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Action plans identify ways of sustaining human well-being, employing natural capital, macroeconomic policies including economic incentives, and ecosystem services.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] In the EU Directive 1999/22/EC zoos are described as having a role in the preservation of the biodiversity of wildlife animals by conducting research or participation in breeding programs.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Removal of exotic species will allow the species that they have negatively impacted to recover their ecological niches.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Exotic species that have become pests can be identified taxonomically (e.g., with Digital Automated Identification SYstem (DAISY), using the barcode of life).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] Removal is practical only given large groups of individuals due to the economic cost.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p01] As sustainable populations of the remaining native species in an area become assured, "missing" species that are candidates for reintroduction can be identified using databases such as the *Encyclopedia of Life* and the Global Biodiversity Information Facility.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Protected areas, including forest reserves and biosphere reserves, serve many functions including for affording protection to wild animals and their habitat.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Protected areas have been set up all over the world with the specific aim of protecting and conserving plants and animals.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Some scientists have called on the global community to designate as protected areas of 30 percent of the planet by 2030, and 50 percent by 2050, in order to mitigate biodiversity loss from anthropogenic causes.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] The target of protecting 30% of the area of the planet by the year 2030 (30 by 30) was adopted by almost 200 countries in the 2022 United Nations Biodiversity Conference.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] At the moment of adoption (December 2022) 17% of land territory and 10% of ocean territory were protected.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] In a study published 4 September 2020 in Science Advances researchers mapped out regions that can help meet critical conservation and climate goals.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Protected areas safeguard nature and cultural resources and contribute to livelihoods, particularly at local level.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] There are over 238 563 designated protected areas worldwide, equivalent to 14.9 percent of the earth's land surface, varying in their extension, level of protection, and type of management (IUCN, 2018).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] The benefits of protected areas extend beyond their immediate environment and time.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] In addition to conserving nature, protected areas are crucial for securing the long-term delivery of ecosystem services.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] They provide numerous benefits including the conservation of genetic resources for food and agriculture, the provision of medicine and health benefits, the provision of water, recreation and tourism, and for acting as a buffer against disaster.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Increasingly, there is acknowledgement of the wider socioeconomic values of these natural ecosystems and of the ecosystem services they can provide.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] A national park is a large natural or near natural area set aside to protect large-scale ecological processes, which also provide a foundation for environmentally and culturally compatible, spiritual, scientific, educational, recreational and visitor opportunities.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] These areas are selected by governments or private organizations to protect natural biodiversity along with its underlying ecological structure and supporting environmental processes, and to promote education and recreation.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] The International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN), and its World Commission on Protected Areas (WCPA), has defined "National Park" as its Category II type of protected areas.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Wildlife sanctuaries are areas of either shelter for animals who are unable to live in the wild on their own, or they are temporary rehabilitation centers for wildlife to improve in their overall health and wellbeing.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Both of these serve as places in which biodiversity can be preserved rather than harmed.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] According to an article published in the National Park Service website, national parks aim their resources at maintaining animal and habitat integrity through conservation and preservation of their ecosystems.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] This along with educating the general public on wildlife functions, the aim for an increase in biodiversity is one of many goals trying to be focused on through national parks.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Forest protected areas are a subset of all protected areas in which a significant portion of the area is forest.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] This may be the whole or only a part of the protected area.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Globally, 18 percent of the world's forest area, or more than 700 million hectares, fall within legally established protected areas such as national parks, conservation areas and game reserves.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] There is an estimated 726 million ha of forest in protected areas worldwide.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Of the six major world regions, South America has the highest share of forests in protected areas, 31 percent.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] The forests play a vital role in harboring more than 45,000 floral and 81,000 faunal species of which 5150 floral and 1837 faunal species are endemic.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] In addition, there are 60,065 different tree species in the world.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Plant and animal species confined to a specific geographical area are called endemic species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] In forest reserves, rights to activities like hunting and grazing are sometimes given to communities living on the fringes of the forest, who sustain their livelihood partially or wholly from forest resources or products.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Approximately 50 million hectares (or 24%) of European forest land is protected for biodiversity and landscape protection.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Forests allocated for soil, water, and other ecosystem services encompass around 72 million hectares (32% of European forest area).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] It stated that "the state of nature has deteriorated at an unprecedented and accelerating rate".
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] To fix the problem, humanity will need a transformative change, including sustainable agriculture, reductions in consumption and waste, fishing quotas and collaborative water management.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] The concept of nature-positive is playing a role in mainstreaming the goals of the Global Biodiversity Framework (GBF) for biodiversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] The aim of mainstreaming is to embed biodiversity considerations into public and private practice to conserve and sustainably use biodiversity on global and local levels.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] The concept of nature-positive refers to the societal goal to halt and reverse biodiversity loss, measured from a baseline of 2020 levels, and to achieve full so-called "nature recovery" by 2050.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Citizen science, also known as public participation in scientific research, has been widely used in environmental sciences and is particularly popular in a biodiversity-related context.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] It has been used to enable scientists to involve the general public in biodiversity research, thereby enabling the scientists to collect data that they would otherwise not have been able to obtain.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Volunteer observers have made significant contributions to on-the-ground knowledge about biodiversity, and recent improvements in technology have helped increase the flow and quality of occurrences from citizen sources.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] A 2016 study published in Biological Conservation registers the massive contributions that citizen scientists already make to data mediated by the Global Biodiversity Information Facility (GBIF).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Despite some limitations of the dataset-level analysis, it is clear that nearly half of all occurrence records shared through the GBIF network come from datasets with significant volunteer contributions.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Recording and sharing observations are enabled by several global-scale platforms, including iNaturalist and eBird.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Global agreements such as the Convention on Biological Diversity, give "sovereign national rights over biological resources" (not property).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] The agreements commit countries to "conserve biodiversity", "develop resources for sustainability" and "share the benefits" resulting from their use.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Biodiverse countries that allow bioprospecting or collection of natural products, expect a share of the benefits rather than allowing the individual or institution that discovers/exploits the resource to capture them privately.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Bioprospecting can become a type of biopiracy when such principles are not respected.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Sovereignty principles can rely upon what is better known as Access and Benefit Sharing Agreements (ABAs).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] The Convention on Biodiversity implies informed consent between the source country and the collector, to establish which resource will be used and for what and to settle on a fair agreement on benefit sharing.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] The agreement includes also recovering 30% of earth degraded ecosystems and increasing funding for biodiversity issues.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] In May 2020, the European Union published its Biodiversity Strategy for 2030.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] The biodiversity strategy is an essential part of the climate change mitigation strategy of the European Union.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] From the 25% of the European budget that will go to fight climate change, large part will go to restore biodiversity and nature based solutions.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Approximately half of the global GDP depend on nature.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] In Europe many parts of the economy that generate trillions of euros per year depend on nature.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] The benefits of Natura 2000 alone in Europe are €200 – €300 billion per year.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Uniform approval for use of biodiversity as a legal standard has not been achieved, however.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] Bosselman argues that biodiversity should not be used as a legal standard, claiming that the remaining areas of scientific uncertainty cause unacceptable administrative waste and increase litigation without promoting preservation goals.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] India passed the Biological Diversity Act in 2002 for the conservation of biological diversity in India.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/biodiversity-p02] The Act also provides mechanisms for equitable sharing of benefits from the use of traditional biological resources and knowledge.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] See Late Quaternary prehistoric birds for birds which disappeared in prehistoric and early historic times, usually due to human activity (i.e., starting with the Upper Paleolithic Revolution).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] For birds having gone extinct in modern times (since 1500), see List of extinct birds.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Since the Late Pleistocene period, it is estimated that 1,430 (95% credible interval: 1327–1544) bird extinctions have occurred.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Human activity has been directly attributed to almost all bird species extinctions, specifically prehistoric and early historical species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] During the Upper Paleolithic period, human societies began spreading across the globe, leading to the overhunting of species and the introduction of invasive species to new environments.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] A particularly significant period of extinction occurred when humans colonized the islands of Melanesia, Polynesia, and Micronesia around 4,000 years ago.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] According to a study published in *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences*, early Polynesian settlers are often credited with contributing to the extinction of over 1,000 bird species during this time, majority of which were non-passerine land birds.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Before the Industrial Revolution (1750-1850), most bird species were not yet heavily impacted by habitat loss or climate change.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] However, overexploitation through hunting, bird collecting, as well as the introduction of invasive species became significant threats.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Industrialization marked a turning point in the relationship between humans and birds.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The technological growth, urban expansion, and increased emissions from industrial activity caused widespread habitat destruction and altered ecosystems.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] In the United Kingdom, species such as the white-tailed eagle (*Haliaeetus albicilla*) and cranes, for example, were recognized as more abundant before industrialization began.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] By the 19th century, the advent of industrial-scale hunting and urban sprawl had put pressure on many bird populations.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The species' final extinction came in the early 20th century, though causes remain unclear.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Similarly, the passenger pigeon (*Ectopistes migratorius*) once one of the most populous bird species in North America, was driven to extinction in the early 20th century due to relentless hunting and habitat loss.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] This extinction served as a stark reminder of the fragility of bird populations in the face of human intervention.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The loss of such a previously abundant species helped catalyze the first major bird conservation efforts in the United States.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Following the assumed extinction of passenger pigeons, Theodore Roosevelt claimed to have witnessed a small flock of the birds at his family name’s rural cabin in Virginia some 25 years after their extinction (March 24, 1900).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Following this sighting, Theodore recognized the severity of the loss of this once abundant species and initiated strengthened bird advocacy legislation during his presidency in 1907.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The establishment of the first Federal Bird Reserve on Pelican Island in Florida can be attributed to this sighting made by President Roosevelt.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The early 20th century saw the rise of formal conservation efforts.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The National Audubon Society, founded in 1905, played a key role in raising awareness about the rapid decline of bird populations, specifically in response to the exploitation of birds for the feather trade.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The organization's efforts were influential in propelling early legal protections for birds.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] A significant achievement in favor of bird protection was the passage of the Migratory Bird Treaty Act of 1918.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] This act provided international protection for migratory bird species between the United States, Canada, Mexico, Japan, and Russia.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] From the 1920s to 1950s, bird advocacy gained further strength.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] It sought to fund the protection of wetlands using hunter fees.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Additionally, during the Great Depression, New Deal programs including the Civilian Conservation Corps preserved wildlife refuges, providing birds a thriving environment for bird species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Birdwatching gained popularity within this timeframe, too, in large part thanks to Roger Tory Peterson’s groundbreaking field guides.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Finally, Rachel Carson's early works began to clarify the relationship between healthy bird populations and a healthy planet.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] All of these factors laid more solid groundwork for the continuation of advocacy for birds.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The 1960s were a particularly pivotal era in favor of bird conservation.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The publication of Rachel Carson’s *Silent Spring* (1962) aided in exposing widespread dangers of pesticide use, particularly DDT, on bird populations.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Her groundbreaking work demonstrated how DDT led to the thinning of eggshells in species like the bald eagle (*Haliaeetus leucocephalus*) and peregrine falcon (*Falco peregrinus*), resulting in reproductive failures.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Carson’s book ignited a broader environmental movement, leading to significant policy changes, and the eventual DDT ban.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The Environmental Protection Agency enforced a generalized ban on DDT pesticides in 1972.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Bald eagles made a famous comeback during the “dirty sixties” thanks to this ban, along with the brown pelican (*Pelecanus occidentalis*) and peregrine falcon.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] By the 1980s, the global conservation movement gained further momentum.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Organizations like BirdLife International played an increasingly vital role in establishing international frameworks for bird protection.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] This included efforts to protect critical habitats, such as wetland areas, and to monitor at-risk species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Additionally, the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) developed the Red List of Threatened Species, which continues to serve as an important tool for identifying and tracking species at risk of extinction, including many bird species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The most critical threat facing threatened birds is the destruction and fragmentation of habitat.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The loss of forests, plains and other natural systems into agriculture, mines, and urban developments, the draining of swamps and other wetlands, and logging reduce potential habitat for many species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] In addition the remaining patches of habitat are often too small or fragmented by the construction of roads or other such barriers that cause populations in these fragmented *islands* to become vulnerable to localized extinction.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] In addition many forest species show limited abilities to disperse and occupy new forest fragments (see island biogeography).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The loss of tropical rainforest is the most pressing problem, as these forests hold the highest number of species yet are being destroyed quickly.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Habitat loss has been implicated in a number of extinctions, including the ivory-billed woodpecker (*Campephilus principalis*) (disputed because of "rediscovery"), Bachman's warbler (*Vermivora bachmanii*), and the dusky seaside sparrow (*Ammospiza maritima nigrescens*).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Climate change is a catalyst for the worrying downward trend of bird populations globally.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The speed of human-caused climate change is currently unprecedented, leading bird species into continuously unadaptable circumstances.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] It has been observed that most North American bird species have been recognized over the prior few decades to have shifted their breeding ranges irregularly due to climate change.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Migratory birds are more prone to the effects of climate change, leading to shifts in time migratory patterns.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] It is predicted in the coming years that mountainous birds will even lose suitable migratory habitats due to rising temperatures at higher elevations.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] On top of these migratory shifts, global warming has been predicted to be changing size and wing length proportionally in all bird species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] It is presumed that with rising temperatures, smaller birds maintain better competitive fitness thanks to their easier heat dispersal compared to their larger counterparts within the same species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Indirect impacts of climate change on birds include increased drought and fires, rising-sea levels, increased disease, phenological mismatch, and uncommon interactions between species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Increase in drought leads to increased fires, destroying nesting ground and fragmenting specifically sagebrush ecosystems.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Rise in sea-levels provides similar altercations for marsh-nesting birds.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Nesting sites disappear as sea-levels rise, eliminating habitats for nesting parents and young to continue species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Phenological mismatch occurs due to rising temperatures shifting migratory timeframes but not quickly enough, altering the life cycle events in interacting species at different rates.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Birds are afflicted by numerous pollutants including marine oil pollution, plastic pollution, light pollution, sound pollution, air pollution, and pesticides to name a major few.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Plastic pollution serves a major detriment to birds, mainly marine birds.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Many marine birds suffer from entanglement, nutritional deprivation, and gut damage due to ingested plastic litter.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Historically the threat posed by introduced species has probably caused the most extinctions of birds, particularly on islands. most prehistoric human caused extinctions were insular as well.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Many island species evolved in the absence of predators and consequently lost many anti-predator behaviors.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] As humans traveled around the world they brought with them many foreign animals which disturbed these island species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Some of these were unfamiliar predators, like rats, feral cats, and pigs; others were competitors, such as other bird species, or herbivores that degraded breeding habitat.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Disease can also play a role; introduced avian malaria is thought to be a primary cause of many extinctions in Hawaii.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Many species currently threatened with extinction are vulnerable to introduced species, such as the kōkako (*Callaeas* species), black robin *(Petroica traversi)*, Mariana crow (*Corvus kubaryi*), and the Hawaiian duck (*Anas wyvilliana*).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Humans have exploited birds for a very long time, and sometimes this exploitation has resulted in extinction.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Overhunting occurred in some instances with a naive species unfamiliar with humans, such as the moa of New Zealand, in other cases it was an industrial level of hunting that led to extinction.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The passenger pigeon was once the most numerous species of bird alive (possibly ever), overhunting reduced a species that once numbered in the billions to extinction.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Hunting pressure can be for food, sport, feathers, or even come from scientists collecting museum specimens.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Collection of great auks for museums pushed the already rare species to extinction.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The harvesting of parrots for the pet trade has led to many species becoming endangered.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Between 1986 and 1988, two million parrots were legally imported into the US alone.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Parrots are also illegally smuggled between countries, and rarer species can command high prices.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Organized entrapment of birds takes place today across the globe, specifically in Latin America, Asia, and Africa.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The demand for exotic pet birds in the United States drives capture in Bolivia and Mexico, with a supposed over 22,000 individuals of 31 parrot species illegally traded under Bolivian law every year and an estimated 65,000–78,500 parrots captured every year in Mexico.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] This poaching continues due to the potential profits, with rarer species selling for up to $1,000 each when caught illegally.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Plume hunting is the hunting of wild birds to harvest their decorative feathers.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] More decorative plumes, which were sold for use as ornamentation particularly in hat-making, were more sought after in the trade.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] While the plume trade is not necessarily a large ongoing threat to birds, it was in its height in the late 19th century into the early 20th century until protective efforts were instated.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Hybridization may also endanger birds, damaging the gene stock.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] For example, the American black duck (*Anas rubripes*) has been often reported hybridizing with the mallard (*Anas platyrhynchos*), starting a slow decline in the rarer *A. rubripes*.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Gamebird hybrids are particularly common and many breeders produce hybrids that may be accidentally or intentionally introduced into the wild.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Pollution has led to serious declines in some species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Increasingly large volumes of plastic waste are being transported by wind and ocean currents throughout the planet, and mistaken ingestion by many species is eventually fatal.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Seabirds are also vulnerable to oil spills, which destroy the plumage's waterproofing, causing the birds to drown or die of hypothermia.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Light pollution can also have a damaging effect on some species, particularly nocturnal seabirds such as petrels.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The pesticide DDT was responsible for thinning egg shells in nesting birds, particularly seabirds and birds of prey that are high on the food chain.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The use of pesticides continues to harm birds, especially insectivores like swallows that have lost a food source from the use of insecticides in agriculture.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] A particularly dangerous class of pesticides is the seed-coating neonicotinoids.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Neonicotinoids include a neurotoxin that bioaccumulates in the tissue of birds and is associated with impairment of reproduction.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Seabirds face another threat in the form of bycatch, where birds in the water become tangled in fishing nets or hooked on lines set out by long-line fisheries.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] As many as 100,000 albatrosses are hooked and drown each year on tuna lines set out by long-line fisheries.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Birds are also threatened by high rise buildings, communications towers, and other human-related activities and structures; estimates vary from about 3.5 to 975 million birds a year in the North America alone.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The largest source of human-related bird death is due to glass windows, which kill 100–900 million birds a year.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The next largest sources of human-caused death are hunting (100+ million), house cats (100 million), cars and trucks (50 to 100 million), electric power lines (174 million), and pesticides (67 million).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Birds are also killed in large quantities by flying into communication tower guidelines, usually after being attracted by tower lights.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] This phenomenon is called towerkill and is responsible for 5–50 million birds deaths a year.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Similarly, natural gas flaring can attract and kill large numbers of birds.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Approximately 7,500 migrating songbirds were attracted to and killed by the flare at the liquefied natural gas terminal in Saint John, New Brunswick, Canada, on September 13, 2013.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Similar incidents have occurred at flares on offshore oil and gas installations.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The recent growth in the renewable energy industry is also increasing the threat to birds farther away from dense human population centers.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] As of late 2019, the capacity of wind power in the U.S. reached 100 GW (gigawatt).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Studies conducted at a variety of farms found fewer than 14, and typically fewer than 4, direct bird deaths per year per installed megawatt; suggesting cumulative mortality is approaching the order of a million individuals annually.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Migrating songbirds appeared to be the most strongly impacted in some studies.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The primary impact of commercial solar farms – the majority utilizing photovoltaic collectors which are mounted near the ground – is from extensive land clearing and increases in long-distance power transmission infrastructure.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] According to a 2018 *Nature* paper studying trends in global waterbird populations, ineffective governance is a major driver of biodiversity loss in wetlands, highlighting the importance of political and institutional factors in conservation outcomes.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Scientists and conservation professionals have developed a number of techniques to protect bird species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] These techniques have had varying levels of success.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Captive breeding, or *ex-situ* conservation, has been used in a number of instances to save species from extinction.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The principle is to create a viable population of a species in either zoos or breeding facilities, for later reintroduction back into the wild.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] A captive population can either serve as an insurance against the species going extinct in the wild or as a last-ditch effort in situations where conservation in the wild is impossible.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Captive breeding has been used to save several species from extinction, the most famous example being the California condor, a species that declined to less than thirty birds.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] In order to save the California condor the decision was made to take every individual left in the wild into captivity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] From these 22 individuals a breeding program began that brought the numbers up to 273 by 2005.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] An even more impressive recovery was that of the Mauritius kestrel (*Falco punctatus*), which by 1974 had dropped to only four individuals, yet by 2006 the population increased to 800.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Reintroductions of captive bred populations can occur to replenish wild populations of an endangered species, to create new populations or to restore a species after it has become extinct in the wild.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Reintroductions helped bring the wild populations of Hawaiian geese (nene) (*Branta sandvicensis)* from 30 birds to over 500.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The Mauritius kestrel was successfully reintroduced into the wild after its captive breeding programme.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Reintroductions can be very difficult and often fail if insufficient preparations are made, as species born in captivity may lack the skills and knowledge needed for life in the wild after living in captivity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Reintroductions can also fail if the causes of a birds decline have not been adequately addressed.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Attempts to reintroduce the Bali starling (*Leucopsar rothschildi*) into the wild failed due to continued poaching of reintroduced birds.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The introduction of captives of unknown pedigree can also pose a threat to native populations.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Domestic fowl have threatened endemic species such as *Gallus g. bankiva* while pheasants such as the ring-necked pheasant (*Phasianus colchicus*) and captive cheer pheasants (*Catreus wallichii*) of uncertain origin have escaped into the wild or have been intentionally introduced.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Green peafowl (*Pavo muticus*) of similar mixed origins confiscated from local bird dealers have been released into areas with native wild birds.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Translocations involve moving populations of threatened species into areas of suitable habitat currently unused by the species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] There are several reasons for doing this; the creation of secondary populations that act as an insurance against disaster, or in many cases threats faced by the original population in its current location.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] One famous translocation was of the kākāpō (*Strigops habroptilus*) of New Zealand.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] These large flightless parrots were unable to cope with introduced predators in their remaining habitat on Stewart Island, so were moved to smaller offshore islands that had been cleared of predators.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] From there a recovery program has managed to maintain and eventually increase their numbers.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] As the loss and destruction of habitat is the most serious threat facing many bird species, conservation organizations and government agencies tasked with protecting birds work to protect areas of natural habitat.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] This can be achieved through purchasing land of conservation importance, setting aside land or gazetting it as a national park or other protected area, and passing legislation preventing landowners from undertaking damaging land use practices, or paying them not to undertake those activities.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] The goals of habitat protection for birds and other threatened animals and plants often conflicts with other stakeholders, such as landowners and businesses, who can face economically damaging restrictions on their activities.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/bird-conservation] Plans to protect crucial habitat for the spotted owl (*Strix occidentalis*) of North America required the protection of large areas of old growth forest in the western United States; this was opposed by logging companies who claimed it would cause job losses and reduced profits.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] For many species, relatively little is known about the conditions needed for successful breeding.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Information about a species' reproductive biology may be critical to the success of a captive breeding program.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] In some cases a captive breeding program can save a species from extinction, but for success, breeders must consider many factors—including genetic, ecological, behavioral, and ethical issues.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Most successful attempts involve the cooperation and coordination of many institutions.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] The efforts put into captive breeding can aid in education about conservation because species in captivity are closer to the public than their wild conspecifics.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] These accomplishments from the continued breeding of species for generations in captivity is also aided by extensive research efforts ex-situ and in-situ.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Captive breeding techniques began with the first human domestication of animals such as goats, and plants like wheat, at least 10,000 years ago.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] These practices were expanded with the rise of the first zoos, which started as royal menageries such as the one at Hierakonpolis, capital in the Predynastic Period of Egypt.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] The first actual captive breeding programs were only started in the 1960s.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] These programs, such as the Arabian Oryx breeding program from the Phoenix Zoo in 1962, were aimed at the reintroduction of these species into the wild.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] These programs expanded under The Endangered Species Act of 1973 of the Nixon Administration which focused on protecting endangered species and their habitats to preserve biodiversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Since then, research and conservation have been housed in zoos, such as the Institute for Conservation Research at the San Diego Zoo founded in 1975 and expanded in 2009, which have contributed to the successful conservation efforts of species such as the Hawaiian Crow.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] The breeding of species of conservation concern is coordinated by cooperative breeding programs containing international studbooks and coordinators, who evaluate the roles of individual animals and institutions from a global or regional perspective.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] These studbooks contain information on birth date, gender, location, and lineage (if known), which helps determine survival and reproduction rates, number of founders of the population, and inbreeding coefficients.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] A species coordinator reviews the information in studbooks and determines a breeding strategy that would produce most advantageous offspring.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] If two compatible animals are found at different zoos, the animals may be transported for mating, but this is stressful, which could in turn make mating less likely.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] However, this is still a popular breeding method among European zoological organizations.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Artificial fertilization (by shipping semen) is another option, but male animals can experience stress during semen collection, and the same goes for females during the artificial insemination procedure.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Furthermore, this approach yields lower-quality semen, because shipping requires extending the life of the sperm for the transit time.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] The objective of many captive populations is to hold similar levels of genetic diversity to what is found in wild populations.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] As captive populations are usually small and maintained in artificial environments, genetics factors such as adaptation, inbreeding and loss of diversity can be a major concern.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Adaptive differences between plant and animal populations arise due to variations in environmental pressures.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] In the case of captive breeding prior to reintroduction into the wild, it is possible for species to evolve to adapt to the captive environment, rather than their natural environment.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Reintroducing a plant or animal to an environment dissimilar to the one they were originally from can cause fixation of traits that may not be suited for that environment leaving the individual disadvantaged.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Selection intensity, initial genetic diversity, and effective population size can impact how much the species adapts to its captive environment.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Modeling works indicate that the duration of the programs (i.e., time from the foundation of the captive population to the last release event) is an important determinant of reintroduction success.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Success is maximized for intermediate project duration allowing the release of a sufficient number of individuals, while minimizing the number of generations undergoing relaxed selection in captivity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Can be minimized by reducing the number of generations in captivity, minimizing selection for captive adaptations by creating environment similar to natural environment and maximizing the number of immigrants from wild populations.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] One consequence of small captive population size is the increased impact of genetic drift, where genes have the potential to fix or disappear completely by chance, thereby reducing genetic diversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Other factors that can impact genetic diversity in a captive population are bottlenecks and initial population size.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Bottlenecks, such as rapid decline in the population or a small initial population impacts genetic diversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Loss can be minimized by establishing a population with a large enough number of founders to genetically represent the wild population, maximize population size, maximize ratio of effective population size to actual population size, and minimize the number of generations in captivity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Inbreeding is when organisms mate with closely related individuals, lowering heterozygosity in a population.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Although inbreeding can be relatively common, when it results in a reduction in fitness it is known as inbreeding depression.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] The detrimental effects of inbreeding depression are especially prevalent in smaller populations and can therefore be extensive in captive populations.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] To make these populations the most viable, it is important to monitor and reduce the effects of deleterious allele expression caused by inbreeding depression and to restore genetic diversity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Comparing inbred populations against non-inbred or less-inbred populations can help determine the extent of detrimental effects if any are present.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Closely monitoring the possibility of inbreeding within the captive bred population is also key to the success of reintroduction into the species' native habitat.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Outbreeding is when organisms mate with unrelated individuals, increasing heterozygosity in a population.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Although new diversity is often beneficial, if there are large genetic differences between the two individuals it can result in outbreeding depression.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] This is a reduction in fitness, similar to that of inbreeding depression, but arises from a number of different mechanisms, including taxonomic issues, chromosomal differences, sexual incompatibility, or adaptive differences between the individuals.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] A common cause is chromosomal ploidy differences and hybridization between individuals leading to sterility.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] The best example is in the orangutan, which, prior to taxonomic revisions in the 1980s would be commonly mated in captive populations producing hybrid orangutans with lower fitness.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] If chromosomal ploidy is ignored during reintroduction, restoration efforts would fail due to sterile hybrids in the wild.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] If there are large genetic differences between individuals originally from distant populations, those individuals should only be bred in circumstances where no other mates exist.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Captive breeding can contribute to changes in behavior in animals that have been reintroduced to the wild.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Released animals are commonly less capable of hunting or foraging for food, which leads to starvation, possibly because the young animals spent the critical learning period in captivity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Released animals often display more risk-taking behavior and fail to avoid predators.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Golden lion tamarin mothers often die in the wild before having offspring because they cannot climb and forage.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] This leads to continuing population declines despite reintroduction as the species are unable to produce viable offspring.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Training can improve anti-predator skills, but its effectiveness varies.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Salmon bred in captivity have shown similar declines in caution and are killed by predators when young.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] However, salmon that were reared in an enriched environment with natural prey showed less risk-taking behaviors and were more likely to survive.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] A study on mice has found that after captive breeding had been in place for multiple generations and these mice were "released" to breed with wild mice, that the captive-born mice bred amongst themselves instead of with the wild mice.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] This suggests that captive breeding may affect mating preferences, and has implications for the success of a reintroduction program.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Human mediated recovery of species can unintentionally promote maladaptive behaviors in wild populations.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] In 1980 the number of wild Chatham Island Black Robins was reduced to a single mating pair.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Intense management of populations helped the population recover and by 1998 there were 200 individuals.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] During recovery scientists observed "rim laying" an egg laying habit where individuals laid eggs on the rim of the nest instead of the center.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] To combat this land managers pushed the egg to the center of the nest, which greatly increased reproduction.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] However, by allowing this maladaptive trait to persist, over half the population were now rim layers.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Genetic studies found that this was an autosomal dominant mendelian trait that was selected for due to human intervention.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Another challenge presented to captive breeding is an attempt to establish multi-partner mating systems in captive populations.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] It can be difficult to replicate the circumstances surrounding multiple mate systems and allow it to occur naturally in captivity due to limited housing space and lack of information.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] When brought into captivity, there is no guarantee that a pair of animals will pair bond or that all the members of a population will participate in breeding.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Throughout facilities, there is limited housing space so allowing for mate choice may establish genetic issues in the population.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] A lack of information surrounding the effects of mating systems on captive populations can also present issues when attempting to breed.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] These mating systems are not always fully understood and the effects captivity may have on them cannot be known until they are studied in greater capacity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] The Phoenix Zoo had an Arabian Oryx breeding program in 1962.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] They were able to successfully breed over 200 individuals from a lineage of only 9 original founders.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Members from this founding population were then sent to many other facilities worldwide, and many breeding herds were established.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] In 1982, the first of the population was reintroduced back into Oman, and over the next two decades, their population increased over time and was able to successfully reestablish in native regions.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Arabian Oryx have now been reintroduced into areas such as Saudi Arabia, Oman, and Israel and they now number 1,100, showing a recovery thanks to captive breeding efforts.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] The De Wildt Cheetah and Wildlife Centre, established in South Africa in 1971, has a cheetah captive breeding program.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Between 1975 and 2005, 242 litters were born with a total of 785 cubs.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] The survival rate of cubs was 71.3% for the first twelve months and 66.2% for older cubs, validating the fact that cheetahs can be bred successfully (and their endangerment decreased).
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] It also indicated that failure in other breeding habitats may be due to "poor" sperm morphology.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Przewalski's horse, the only horse species never to have been domesticated, was recovered from the brink of extinction by a captive breeding program, and successfully reintroduced in the 1990s to the Mongolia, with more than 750 wild roaming Przewalski's horses as of 2020.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] The Galápagos tortoise population, once reaching as low in population as 12 remaining individuals, as of 2014 was recovered to more than 2000 by a captive breeding program.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] A further 8 tortoise species were supported by captive breeding programs in the island chain.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Wild Tasmanian devils have declined by 90% due to a transmissible cancer called Devil Facial Tumor Disease.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] A captive insurance population program was started, but the captive breeding rates as of 2012 were lower than they needed to be.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Keeley, Fanson, Masters, and McGreevy (2012) sought to "increase our understanding of the estrous cycle of the devil and elucidate potential causes of failed male-female pairings" by examining temporal patterns of fecal progestogen and corticosterone metabolite concentrations.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] They found that the majority of unsuccessful females were captive-born, suggesting that if the species' survival depended solely on captive breeding, the population would probably disappear.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] In 2010, the Oregon Zoo found that Columbia Basin pygmy rabbit pairings based on familiarity and preferences resulted in a significant increase in breeding success.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] In 2019, researchers trying to breed captive American paddlefish and Russian sturgeon separately inadvertently bred sturddlefish - a hybrid fish between the two fish.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Captive breeding can also be a research tool to understand the reproductive physiology and reproductive behaviors of species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] In order to successfully breed animals, there must be an understanding of their mating systems, their reproductive physiology, and behavior or mating rituals.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Through captive breeding programs, these factors can be measured in a finite setting and the results can be interpreted and used to aid in ex-situ and in-situ conservation.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Through a greater understanding of these systems, captive breeding efforts can have greater success when attempting to reproduce a species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] A lot of research about elephant reproductive physiology and estrus cycles has been conducted in captivity and a greater understanding of how these factors play into breeding attempts can be established.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Behavioral research quantifies the effects of how estrus plays a role in the herds behaviors and how this effects the bulls of a herd.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] This research can help facilities monitor for behavior changes in their herd and conduct successful breeding attempts through this understanding.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Research helps with better understanding these physiological systems which in turn helps increase successful breeding attempts and allows for more generations to be brought up in captivity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Not only does physiological research aid in captive breeding attempts, but multi-generational research is also another important research tool that is conducted on different species and genetic changes can be tracked through different lineages brought up in captivity.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Genetic changes throughout a specific lineage can help provide breeding recommendations and allow for genetic diversity within a captive population to remain high.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] This genetic record keeping is also used in order to understand phylogeny and to better understand fitness changes that may occur over generations in captive populations.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] This form of record keeping helps aid in research surrounding population genetics in order to evaluate the best method to sustain high genetic variation within captive populations.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Research conducted on captive breeding populations is also important when creating SAFE's and SSP's for a certain species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Studies in behavior are important when developing captive breeding programs because they allow facilities to understand an animals response to captivity and allows facilities to adapt proper housing conditions for the animals.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Populations that are currently being propagated in captivity are very important research tools for understanding how to carry out successful propagation of a certain species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] This research allows the knowledge to be passed on to more facilities allowing for more breeding programs to be developed in order to increase the genetic diversity of captive populations.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] The research conducted on breeding populations is also an important gateway into understanding other aspects of an animal such as social dynamics, nutrition and diet requirements, and demographics to allow for captive populations to prosper.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] To found a captive breeding population with adequate genetic diversity, breeders usually select individuals from different source populations—ideally, at least 20–30 individuals.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Founding populations for captive breeding programs have often had fewer individuals than ideal because of their threatened state, leaving them more susceptible to challenges such as inbreeding depression.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] To overcome challenges of captive breeding such as adaptive differences, loss of genetic diversity, inbreeding depression, and outbreeding depression and get desired results, captive breeding programs use many monitoring methods.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Artificial insemination is used to produce the desired offspring from individuals who do not mate naturally to reduce effects of mating closely related individuals such as inbreeding.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Methods as seen in panda pornography allow programs to mate chosen individuals by encouraging mating behavior.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] A concern in captive breeding is to minimize the effects of breeding closely related individuals, microsatellite regions from an organism's genome can be used to determine amounts of relationship among founders to minimize relatedness and pick the most distant individuals to breed.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] This method has successfully been used in the captive breeding of the California condor and the Guam rail.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] The maximum avoidance of inbreeding (MAI) scheme allows control at a group level rather than an individual level by rotating individuals between groups to avoid inbreeding.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Facilities can use intensive housing compared to group housing to allow for easier reproductive success and create more genetic diversity within a population.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Intensive housing is when a species is forced into monogamy so only two individuals mate with each other, compared to group housing where the entire population is kept in the same space to try and replicate multi-partner breeding systems.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] When using intensive housing and forcing monogamy to take place, it is seen that inbreeding is lowered and a greater genetic diversity results.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Intensive housing efforts were used with Tasmanian Devil populations in captivity compared to allowing for group mate choice.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] This helped increase the populations reproductive success in captivity and saw less inbreeding depression within the population.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Using intensive housing to help establish a genetically healthy population in captivity can allow facilities to further increase conservation efforts of a species and combat genetic issues that may arise in the captive population.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Getting captive wild animals to breed naturally can be a difficult task.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Giant pandas for example lose interest in mating once they are captured, and female giant pandas only experience estrus once a year, which only lasts for 48 to 72 hours.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Many researchers have turned to artificial insemination in an attempt to increase the populations of endangered animals.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] It may be used for many reasons, including to overcome physical breeding difficulties, to allow a male to inseminate a much larger number of females, to control the paternity of offspring, and to avoid injury incurred during natural mating.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] It also creates more genetically diverse captive populations, enabling captive facilities to easily share genetic material with each other without the need to move animals.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Scientist of the Justus-Liebig-University of Giessen, Germany, from the working group of Michael Lierz, developed a novel technique for semen collection and artificial insemination in parrots producing the world's first macaw by assisted reproduction.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Animal species can be preserved in gene banks, which consist of a cryogenic facilities used to store live sperm, eggs, or embryos in ultracold conditions.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] The Zoological Society of San Diego has established a "frozen zoo" to store frozen tissue from the world's rarest and most endangered species samples using cryopreservation techniques.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] At present, there has been more than 355 species, including mammals, reptiles, and birds.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Cryopreservation can be performed as oocyte cryopreservation before fertilization, or as embryo cryopreservation after fertilization.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Cryogenically preserved specimens can potentially be used to revive breeds that are endangered or extinct, for breed improvement, crossbreeding, research and development.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] This method can be used for virtually indefinite storage of material without deterioration over a much greater time-period relative to all other methods of *ex situ* conservation.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] However, cryo-conservation can be an expensive strategy and requires long term hygienic and economic commitment for germplasms to remain viable.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Cryo-conservation can also face unique challenges based on the species, as some species have a reduced survival rate of frozen germplasm, but cryobiology is a field of active research and many studies concerning plants are underway.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] An example of the use of cryoconservation to prevent the extinction of a livestock breed is the case of the Hungarian Grey cattle, or Magya Szurke.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Hungarian Grey cattle were once a dominant breed in southeastern Europe with a population of 4.9 million head in 1884.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] They were mainly used for draft power and meat.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] However, the population had decreased to 280,000 head by the end of World War II and eventually reached the low population of 187 females and 6 males from 1965 to 1970.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] The breed's decreased use was due primarily to the mechanization of agriculture and the adoption of major breeds, which yield higher milk production.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] The Hungarian government launched a project to preserve the breed, as it possesses valuable traits, such as stamina, calving ease, disease resistance, and easy adaptation to a variety of climates.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] The government program included various conservation strategies, including the cryopreservation of semen and embryos.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] The Hungarian government's conservation effort brought the population up to 10,310 in 2012, which shows significant improvement using cryoconservation.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] The best current cloning techniques have an average success rate of 9.4 percent, when working with familiar species such as mice, while cloning wild animals is usually less than 1 percent successful.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] In 2001, a cow named Bessie gave birth to a cloned Asian gaur, an endangered species, but the calf died after two days.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] In 2003, a banteng was successfully cloned, followed by three African wildcats from a thawed frozen embryo.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] These successes provided hope that similar techniques (using surrogate mothers of another species) might be used to clone extinct species.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Anticipating this possibility, tissue samples from the last bucardo (Pyrenean ibex) were frozen in liquid nitrogen immediately after it died in 2000.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Researchers are also considering cloning endangered species such as the giant panda and cheetah.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] However, cloning of animals is opposed by animal-groups due to the number of cloned animals that suffer from malformations before they die.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] A potential technique for aiding in reproduction of endangered species is interspecific pregnancy, implanting embryos of an endangered species into the womb of a female of a related species, carrying it to term.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] It has been used for the Spanish Ibex and Houbara bustard.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Captive breeding is an important tool used in modern education of conservation issues because it provides a framework for how we care about species and allows institutions to show the beauty that is contained in our natural environment.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] These practices of captive breeding can be used to explain the function of the modern-day facilities and their importance in conservation.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Through continued breeding efforts populations can continue to be displayed in closer proximity to the public and their role in conservation can be explained.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] These explanations help show a side of the world many people will not engage with because conservation is not something that is inherently known about, it must be shown and taught to others to raise awareness of the issues around the globe.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] By allowing people to view these species in captivity, it allows facilities to explain the issues they face in the wild and advocate for the conservation of these species and their natural habitats.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Institutions focus efforts on large charismatic species, such as elephants, giraffes, rhinos etc., because these draw more visitors to institutions and garner more attention from the public.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] While a lot of these charismatic megafauna do draw more attention than other species, we can still use captive breeding programs and facilities involving other species to educate the public about a broader range of issues.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Bristol Zoo Gardens in the United Kingdom has maintained a species of medicinal leech (*Hirudo medicinalis*) in their facility to use as an education exhibit.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Leeches normally have a negative connotation surrounded by them but they have been used as an important tool in medicine.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] The display at Bristol Zoo Gardens provides an educational piece and tells the story of a woman who sold leeches to the locals around her for medicinal purposes.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] This display advocates for a smaller species that would not normally be covered by facilities, but they are well maintained in this facility and are active conservation of the species is being done because of its significance around humans and in the environment.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] With successes, captive-breeding programs have proven successful throughout history.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Notable examples include the American black-footed ferret; in 1986, a dwindling wild population of only 18 was eventually raised to 500.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] From these actions, those eleven oryx were successfully bred from the brink of extinction, and would go on to be re-released in the deserts of Jordan, Oman, Bahrain, United Arab Emirates and Qatar.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Starting in 1980, the first animals were set free.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Currently, the wild animals number around 1,000 individuals, with a further 6,000-7,000 in zoos and breeding centres internationally.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] While captive breeding can be an ideal solution for preventing endangered animals from facing serious threats of extinction there are still reasons why these programs can occasionally do more harm than good.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Although it has been proven that captive breeding programs have yielded negative genetic effects in decreasing the fitness of captive-bred organisms, there is no direct evidence to show that this negative effect also decreases the overall fitness of their wild-born descendants.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Additionally, there are many ethical complications to reintroducing animals born in captivity back into the wild.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] For example, when scientists were reintroducing a rare species of toad back into the Mallorcan wild in 1993, a potentially deadly fungus that could kill frogs and toads was unintentionally introduced.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] It is also important to maintain the organism's original habitat, or replicate that specific habitat for species survival.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] There are ethical issues surrounding if a species truly needs human intervention and if the resources going toward the captive breeding of these species cannot be allocated to other areas.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Some populations may not need intervention because they were never extinction-prone in the first place such as the peregrine falcon.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] The population of peregrine falcons had a crash in the 1950s and 1960s due to the effect of pesticides on egg production and species survival, causing a decline in the population.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] Many facilities at the time in the U.S. and in European countries brought in peregrine falcons in order to help their declining population and establish a steady population through captive breeding.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] It was later shown through research conducted on the reproductive success of Peregrine Falcons and an analysis of their population that human intervention was not necessary in order for the population to recover and reach a steady point of equilibrium.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] This raises the question of should efforts on captive breeding and population establishment be done with human intervention or should efforts be carried out to prevent the source of the issue.
[src:assisted-natural-regeneration/captive-breeding] The efforts and finances used to help bring about new Peregrine Falcon populations could have been used to prevent some level of pollution or to help breeding effort for extinction-prone species who truly need intervention.
